<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Hijack-Hostage     12-03 0309</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hijack-Hostage,0319</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hostage Says He Did His Duty, Gave Hijackers `A Lift' To Israel</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TEL AVIV, Israel (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Soviet flight engineer who was part of
the crew that flew five hijackers to Israel said he wasn't
threatened by the armed captors and merely ``gave them a lift.''
   Yuri N. Yermilov appeared relaxed as he spoke from the door of
the jet Friday less than an hour after the hijackers surrendered to
Israeli police at Ben-Gurion Airport.
   He signed autographs for Israeli reporters and agreed to be
photographed with a Hebrew-language magazine in his hands.
   The hijackers were flown to Israel after seizing a bus with 30
children in the Soviet Union and trading it for a plane, crew and
$3.3 million ransom.
   ``They were playing cards,'' during the flight, Yermilov said.
``At some point, some of them were in the cockpit behind us, and
they were watching us. They had guns, but they were not waving them
around and threatening us.''
   A younger crew member, who did not give his name, added: ``They
were counting the money.''
   Yermilov, who wore a dark blue Aeroflot uniform, said the
hijackers appeared to be in their 30s. He said they never said why
they chose Israel as their destination.
   ``They were people who wanted to fly out of the Soviet Union.
That's why they kidnapped the bus with children,'' Yermilov said.
   ``They asked for a lift for Israel, and we gave them a lift,'' he
added jokingly.
   He said the crew was appointed for the mission by Soviet
authorities.
   ``We are international pilots. We understood that we have a
mission that has to be done,'' Yermilov said, adding that the crew
was aware of the danger.
   ``We were told that our guarantees are zero. But they (the
hijackers) seemed quite good-natured,'' he said.
</TEXT>
