<1ST_LINE>d a PM-BRF--BeautifulRobber     12-03 0170</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Beautiful Robber,0174</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bank Robber Dubbed `Miss America' Convicted of Five Holdups</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 23-year-old beauty parlor employee was
convicted of robbing five suburban banks during her off hours,
earning her a nickname as the ``Miss America'' bandit among
authorities.
   Danielle Tyece Mast was also known as the ``American Beauty''
bandit, because of the assorted wigs, cosmetics and sunglasses she
wore during a series of heists that began July 15, Assistant U.S.
Attorney William Price said.
   Mast, who was convicted Friday, robbed banks in Manhattan Beach,
Culver City and Torrance, mostly on her lunch hour, after work and
once on a day off from her job at the Touch of Elegance beauty
parlor in Hawthorne, Price said.
   U.S. District Judge A. Andrew Hauk set sentencing for March 27.
   Sentencing was set for March 27, 1989, by U.S. District Judge A.
Andrew Hauk. Mast, who remains free on $50,000 bail, faces a
sentence of up to 100 years in prison and a $1.2 million fine, Price
said.
