<1ST_LINE>r i PM-RevolutionRemembered     12-03 0159</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Revolution Remembered,0162</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>French Revolution Remembered, With Guillotine</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The resort city of Brighton will mark the
bicentennial of the French Revolution next year with an exhibit
including such historical items as a working guillotine.
   The south coast city on Friday announced the exhibit will open in
May.
   Portraits, costumes, documents, furniture and jewelry have been
borrowed from France, the United States, Austria, Sweden and from
British collections to tell the story of the revolution, which began
in 1789.
   Visitors will walk through a series of scenes showing the lives
of ordinary people as well as the court and politics, coming finally
to the foot of the guillotine.
   ``The visitor becomes part of the mob and hears the roll of drums
and the roar of the crowd as the blade crashes down _ and we will
have a quick escape route there for anyone who feels nervous,'' said
organizer Jane Cox.
   The show begins May 4.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
