<FILEID>AP-NR-12-03-88 0346EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Spain-Jaywalker     12-03 0190</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Spain-Jaywalker,0194</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Upholds Ruling Against Jaywalker; Damages to Britons</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FUENGIROLA, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An appeals court upheld a jaywalker's
conviction and $163,237 in damages awarded a British couple
seriously injured in an accident linked to the jaywalking, an
attorney said.
   The attorney for the couple, Alfredo Herrera, told The Associated
Press the appeals court Friday also upheld the $176 fine imposed on
Robert Williamson, 47, of Glasgow, Scotland.
   Williamson's insurance company was ordered to pay damages to
Thomas Usher, 54, and his wife Claire, 53, of London, for injuries
they suffered Sept. 26, 1986, in Mijas, in southern Spain.
   Herrera said the decision affirmed a court ruling in May that
Williamson's jaywalking on a coastal highway caused a heavy truck to
swerve to avoid him and to hit two cars.
   The accident killed a paramilitary Civil Guard officer and
seriously injured a second officer riding with him. The Ushers were
in the second car, and both were seriously injured.
   The court also upheld civil damages of $247,700 to the widow and
family of the Civil Guard officer who died and $74,300 to the
injured Civil Guard, Herrera said.
</TEXT>
