<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Judge-Molester     12-03 0280</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Judge-Molester,0288</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Who Blamed Molester's Wife Resigns</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge who suggested a child molester was driven
to his crimes by his wife's pregnancy has resigned, the lord
chancellor said, but he offered to quit before he made his
controversial comments.
   The announcement Friday said that Judge Sir Harold Cassel
submitted his resignation Monday and cited health reasons. On
Tuesday, Cassel set off a furor by giving two years probation to a
30-year-old man who admitted three indecent assaults on his
adolescent stepdaughter.
   ``It is regrettable that a judge should have expressed himself in
a way that suggested that there are any circumstances that can
excuse or condone indecent assault on children,'' said Lord Mackay,
who as lord chancellor is chief of Britain's judicial system.
   Cassel, 72, became a judge 12 years ago.
   The defendant admitted twice molesting the girl when she was 12
and a third time when the girl was 13 and the mother was in the last
month of pregnancy.
   The mother's condition, Cassel said, led to a ``lack of sexual
appetite in the lady and considerable problems for a healthy young
husband.''
   The judge traced the abuse to the mother's efforts to overcome
the girl's resentment of the new man in the house.
   ``The stepmother encouraged the girl to cuddle her husband and
even got into the habit of inviting her into the marital bed,'' the
judge said. ``This was not an invitation to a toddler, but to a girl
approaching puberty, and the cuddles began to go too far.''
   The mother has filed for divorce.
   More than 20 members of Parliament, including lawmakers from all
major parties, called for Cassel's resignation.
</TEXT>
