<FILEID>AP-NR-12-03-88 0504EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Fernald Bjt   12-03 0690</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Fernald, Bjt,0713</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ohio Announces Fernald Cleanup Agreement</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN NOLAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A historic agreement giving Ohio the authority
to regulate the federal cleanup of a uranium plant was panned by
some neighbors, who plan to pursue their lawsuit against the nuclear
weapons factory.
   Some Fernald residents complained that the agreement between the
U.S. Energy Department and Ohio approved by a federal judge Friday
fails to commit the agency to spending the $1 billion it estimates
is needed for the cleanup.
   ``I don't really see a commitment that cleanup will be done and I
don't see a timetable as to when it will be done,'' said Lisa
Crawford, spokeswoman for Fernald Residents for Environmental Safety
and Health.
   Residents also pointed out that the pact provides no money for
victims of alleged radioactive contamination from the plant, and
that the state has agreed to give up any right to sue the Energy
Department or factory contractors.
   But officials said the consent decree approved here by U.S.
District Judge S. Arthur Spiegel is a historic document allowing
Ohio to enforce state environmental regulatory power over the
cleanup of the plant, which processes uranium for nuclear weapons
assembled elsewhere.
   The agreement also requires the department to pay the state about
$1 million in penalties and to reimburse Ohio for overseeing the
cleanup.
   The Energy Department has admitted that the plant emitted
radioactive uranium dust into the atmosphere over three decades. The
plant, known as the Feed Materials Production Center, sits on 1,050
acres 18 miles northwest of Cincinnati above the Great Miami River
aquifer, a water source for 2 million people.
   Jim Alexander, spokesman for the Energy Department's Oak Ridge,
Tenn., operations, which include Fernald, said the agreement is
evidence of intent to clean up the plant. He said it is not intended
as an admission of wrongdoing.
   Sen. John Glenn, D-Ohio, who announced the agreement with Ohio
Attorney General Anthony Celebrezze Jr., said he hoped the decree
will prompt Congress to give high priority to cleanups of 17 Energy
Department plants nationwide, including Fernald.
   Glenn said the Energy Department estimates it will cost $175
billion to clean up the 17 sites over the next 35 years. Only $300
million is budgeted for the job next year, he said.
   Celebrezze and Ohio Environmental Protection Agency Director
Richard Shank said Ohio will pursue two federal lawsuits against the
Energy Department. The agreement grew out of two years of
negotiations in those cases.
   Stanley Chesley, a Cincinnati lawyer for the plant's neighbors,
said the settlement gives the state no authority over radioactive
wastes stored at the plant.
   Chesley said the neighbors will proceed with their $300 million
class-action suit at a U.S. District Court hearing Dec. 16 in
Cincinnati.
   ``We have every intention of going forward,'' he said.
   Plant neighbor Marvin Clawson, who's represented in the
class-action lawsuit, said the agreement falls short of what the
Energy Department should do.
   ``It mainly addressed the hazardous-waste problem, not the
radioactive waste problem,'' said Clawson, who lives four miles from
the plant. ``They've hardly admitted to anything yet.''
   Celebrezze and Glenn said the decree is historic because it gives
a state a court-enforceable order with which to pressure the Energy
Department to clean up a nuclear facility
   ``The decree also extends Ohio's jurisdiction over Fernald to all
state and federal hazardous-waste law and regulations,'' Celebrezze
said.
   Both men said it is the first such agreement they know of in the
nation.
   The 37-year-old plant has supplied uranium to the Energy
Department's Rocky Flats plant in Colorado, the Hanford reactors in
Washington state, the Savannah River plant in South Carolina and the
Oak Ridge nuclear complex. The Savannah River reactors are shut down
because of problems there, and the closure of the Rocky Flats plant
is reportedly being considered.
   The Fernald plant has been halted by a strike that began Oct. 7.
Energy Department officials have said they expect production to
resume when the strike ends, but declined to comment on the plant's
long-term status. A department report is due out Dec. 15 on the
status of aging nuclear weapons plants nationwide.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
