<1ST_LINE>r a PM-StuckElevator     12-03 0258</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Stuck Elevator,0268</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Four Stuck In Elevator Overnight</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LA CROSSE, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four people freed from a stalled elevator
after spending the night said they kept their spirits up by playing
cards and imagining worse predicaments.
   The four were freed Friday morning after more than 14 hours in
the 4-foot-square elevator in this Mississippi River city.
   ``We were trying to decide what would be worse than this,'' Karen
Nordgren, 34, said. ``So I asked everyone, Would you rather go into
major surgery or go through this again? We all decided surgery.''
   Nordgren, Sandra Lehmann, 39; Adeline ``Kitty'' Reinhart, 59; and
her husband, Raymond, 59, said they shared vitamin C tablets and a
common toilet made from a plastic shopping bag neatly tied and
tucked in a corner.
   Nordgren and Lehmann are beauticians at a third-floor beauty shop
in the building.
   ``Normally, we never take the elevator when we leave,'' Nordgren
said. But she and Lehmann decided to enter the elevator because the
Reinharts were already in it and were holding the door for them, she
said.
   The elevator became stuck shortly before 6 p.m. Thursday.
   ``I didn't think that I was going to get out of there alive,''
Lehmann said.
   She said she eventually overcame her panic and tore a metal plate
from a telephone box inside the elevator. She then used it to pry
open the elevator door, so fresh air could enter the elevator.
   The four were not discovered until shortly after 7 a.m., when the
owner of a business in the building arrived.
</TEXT>
