<1ST_LINE>u a PM-BoardwalkPerformer Bjt   12-03 0515</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Boardwalk Performer, Bjt,0531</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Quadriplegic Woman Who Plays Keyboard With Mouth Challenging
Anti-begging Law</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOYCE A. VENEZIA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTIC CITY, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A quadriplegic woman who says she
makes $2,000 a week playing an electric organ with her mouth is
challenging the city's anti-begging ordinance so she can continue
her Boardwalk performances in front of casinos.
   Celestine Tate's Municipal Court hearing was postponed Friday,
but her lawyers said they were confident they can reach an
out-of-court agreement with the city.
   The 33-year-old woman solicits money from tourists by playing a
portable electric keyboard with her tongue and lips. Birth defects
left her arms and legs undeveloped, and family members move her on a
gurney.
   Ms. Tate said she averages $2,000 a week, enough to send her two
daughters to private school.
   In the past several years, she has accumulated dozens of
summonses from police enforcing this gambling resort's anti-begging
ordinance.
   On Friday, she was in court to face 23 more.
   Ms. Tate's attorneys presented a motion challenging the
ordinance's constitutionality on grounds that it violates her right
of self-expression.
   ``There is a constitutional right to express oneself artistically
and musically,'' argued attorney Justin Loughry.
   City Prosecutor Steven Smoger said he had inadequate time to
review the last-minute motion, and said it should be dismissed.
   Judge Bruce F. Weekes agreed to delay the hearing to give Smoger
time to go over the motion and to give Ms. Tate's attorneys time to
continue negotiating with the city.
   ``I feel like my head is still on the chopping block, because
what they decide will determine my future and my life,'' Ms. Tate
said afterward. ``I believe that the Lord knows somebody's rights
were violated, so he sent me here to prove it.''
   Ms. Tate said that even though the matter is unresolved, she will
return to the Boardwalk today to perform.
   Smoger had been prepared to argue that Ms. Tate violated an
agreement made with the city two years ago.
   After a Superior Court trial in 1986, a subsequent lawsuit and a
lot of publicity, the city agreed to allow Ms. Tate to perform on
the Boardwalk. The conditions were that she must stay near Arkansas
Avenue and obtain a permit.
   Smoger said Friday that Ms. Tate had done neither.
   ``Apparently she became disgruntled because Caesar's
(hotel-casino) was hiring outdoor bands and it cut into her
gratuities, so she moved in front of fire doors at Bally's (Park
Place Casino Hotel),'' Smoger said.
   Ms. Tate acknowledged that she failed to buy insurance for a
permit. Her attorney, Joan Freedman Meyer, said the city offered her
standard one-day Boardwalk permits normally used for parades, which
require a $1 million insurance bond.
   ``That's an unreasonable demand on someone who just plays the
keyboard with her tongue,'' Ms. Meyer said. ``The rolling chairs on
the Boardwalk are only required to carry a $300,000 policy, and
they're carrying passengers.''
   Smoger agreed with Ms. Tate's lawyers that the 1986 agreement was
vaguely worded. ``But even if this is resolved, we still have to
settle the charges,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
