<1ST_LINE>u i PM-India-Bhopal     12-03 0525</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-India-Bhopal,0543</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hundreds Arrested After Bhopal Protesters Throw Stones At Police</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BHARAT DESAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BHOPAL, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of shantytown dwellers hurled rocks
at police who prevented them from storming the Union Carbide
pesticide plant today, the fourth anniversary of a gas leak that
killed more than 3,300 people.
   Police said they arrested at least 200 of the demonstrators.
Protest organizers put the arrest total at 500.
   Most of the protesters, estimated by reporters to number 1,000,
came from shantytowns lying in the path of the deadly white cloud of
methyl isocyanate that leaked out of the plant Dec. 3, 1984.
   A few demonstrators suffered minor injuries in scuffles with
police, who carried steel-tipped bamboo canes but no firearms. There
was no sign of injuries to police.
   Five activists from the Communist Party of India broke away from
police and scaled the 8-foot-high wall surrounding the derelict
factory complex, but four of them were grabbed by plainclothes
police.
   The fifth succeeded in climbing a watchtower and briefly hoisted
the party flag before police hauled him and the red banner away.
   ``We want justice! We want justice!'' the crowd shouted in Hindi.
Some called for the public hanging of Warren Anderson, who was
president of the U.S.-based multinational corporation when the gas
leak occurred.
   Last year, the Indian government filed murder charges against
Anderson and other Union Carbide officials in India and abroad in
conjunction with its $3 billion damage suit against the Danbury,
Conn.-based company.
   The damage suit, initiated in 1986, has bogged down in a maze of
legal maneuvers in courts in Madhya Pradesh state, which includes
Bhopal, and in the Supreme Court in New Delhi. Anderson and the
others have not responded to summonses on the murder charges.
   Effigies of Anderson were set ablaze outside the Bhopal plant
Friday night and again today.
   The Communist Party was the most visible organizer of today's
protests, but other opposition parties and activist groups
campaigning for the rights of gas victims participated in vigils at
the plant gates.
   Balkrishna Gupta, the Communist Party secretary for Madhya
Pradesh state, said 500 demonstrators were arrested.
   Police Superintendent Panna Lal said, ``A couple hundred have
been arrested, but we have not yet made a head count.''
   Reporters who watched the arrested being taken away in eight
government buses estimated the total at 400.
   Police sources who spoke on condition of anonymity said the
demonstrators would be released without charge within a few hours.
Such detentions are legal under Indian law and are commonly used to
break up protests.
   About 500 uniformed police were on hand for the demonstration.
Some had tear gas but did not use it.
   The government says the official death toll from the 1984 gas
leak has reached 3,329.
   Gas Relief Commissioner S. Saytam, a state official whose office
records the deaths and administers relief, said gas victims continue
to die at a rate of at least one a day.
   About 20,000 survivors still suffer from exposure to the gas.
Most say they have respiratory and eye problems.
   Union Carbide said the leak was caused by sabotage by a
disgruntled employee.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
