<2ND_LINE>PM-Bangladesh-Cyclone, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0437,0384</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Search Continues, Death Count At 1,300</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: LEADS with 8 grafs updating death toll. Pickup 9th, `President
Hussain...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By FARID HOSSAIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DHAKA, Bangladesh (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Searchers traveled the river deltas and
channels of southern Bangladesh today looking for more than 3,000
people missing after a cyclone that killed at least 1,300 people.
   Officials said the death toll from Tuesday night's cyclone had
reached 900 in Bangladesh and 400 in India's neighboring West Bengal
state. Dhaka newspapers said the Bangladesh toll may be as high as
1,500.
   The core of the cyclone and the hardest winds struck the lightly
populated Sunderbans forest, an expanse of mangrove trees that
sprawls across the Bangladesh-India border. Officials who spoke on
condition of anonymity said most of the forest dwellers were safe.
   But fishermen who had established colonies along the Sunderbans
coast were hit hard. The independent Ittefaq newspaper said hundreds
of bodies were seen floating in the Sunderbans channels and in the
river deltas of Khulna and Bagerhat districts east of the forest
region.
   Ali Hasan Quereshi, secretary-general of the Bangladesh Red
Crescent Society, said the death toll had reached 900 and may exceed
1,000.
   Another official at the Red Crescent, the Moslem equivalent of
the Red Cross, said 3,000 people, mostly fishermen, were missing.
The official spoke on condition of anonymity.
   Bangladeshi newspapers reported death tolls ranging from 1,000 to
1,500.
   In India, West Bengal Finance Minister Asim Dasgupta said 400
deaths had been officially confirmed, United News of India reported.
   President Hussain Muhammad Ershad of Bangladesh called a special
Cabinet meeting Sunday to discuss relief and rehabilitation efforts.
   Bangladesh officials and foreign relief workers estimated that 40
percent to 70 percent of the rice crop, the staple in the national
diet, was destroyed or damaged by the storm.
   The Sunderbans forest is the home of the royal Bengal tiger, but
there were no official reports of tiger deaths. The Ittefaq
newspaper, however, said hundreds of animals were killed in the
Sunderbans.
   Tiger deaths in the forest have gone unreported in the past.
Newspapers have said game wardens like to sell the tiger pelts, and
if they reported tiger deaths they might have to give the pelts to
the government.
</TEXT>
