<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Tibet-China     12-03 0320</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Tibet-China,0329</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Difficulties Reported In Proposed Tibet-China Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TSETEN SAMDUP</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A proposal for direct talks between
Tibetan and Chinese leaders on the future of Tibet is running into
serious difficulties, sources close to Tibet's government-in-exile
said today.
   The sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the Chinese
appear reluctant to meet in Geneva in January, as proposed by the
Tibetans, and would prefer to meet in Beijing, a venue long rejected
by the Tibetan side.
   The sources suggested a Beijing venue would portray the Tibetan
issue as an internal Chinese matter, rather than an international
one that could be perceived as Chinese recognition of Tibetan
demands for self-rule.
   China invaded Tibet in 1949 and annexed it a year later.
   Many Tibetans have long insisted on independence for their
Himalayan mountain region, but their spiritual and temporal leader,
the Dalai Lama, suggested in June that Tibet could become ``a
self-governing democratic politicial entity ... in association with
China.''
   In his biggest concession so far, the Dalai Lama also said China
could continue to handle Tibet's foreign relations and keep troops
on Tibetan soil.
   Senior Tibetan officials in India declined to confirm the reports
that the Chinese were reluctant to meet in Geneva. But Lodi Gyari,
minister for information and international relations in the
self-styled government-in-exile, said: ``We are not denying them.''
   The Chinese Embassy in New Delhi had no reply to the report. The
embassy's chief spokeswoman was out of town, and an aide said no one
else could comment.
   The reports of Chinese reluctance to meet a Tibetan delegation in
Geneva surfaced after the Dalai Lama's Cabinet convened a special
meeting in Dharmsala on Nov. 25. The meeting was attended by the
Dalai Lama's elder brother, Gyalo Thondup, who had just returned
from Beijing.
   Thondup, a Hong Kong-based businessman, has long served as a
go-between for the Tibetans and Chinese.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
