<1ST_LINE>r a PM-WelfareSettlement 1stLd-Writethru a0459 12-03 0450</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Welfare Settlement, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0459,0461</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Feds Change Loan-as-Income Policy After Nevada Lawsuit</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 1 graf after 3rd graf to ADD HHS comment.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LAURA MYERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RENO, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The federal government has reversed its policy
of counting loans as income for welfare recipients after a Nevada
lawsuit showed the practice violated the law since its inception
five years ago, officials said.
   The lawsuit and similar cases in other states, including
California, prompted the U.S. Department of Health and Human
Services to chang the policy Tuesday, according to a motion filed
Friday in U.S. District Court.
   ``We feel good. We feel real good,'' said attorney Jon Sasser of
Nevada Legal Services, which represents poor people.
   Health and Human Services spokesman Campbell Gardett said he
could not say how many people nationally would be affected by the
policy change.
   The motion filed by Assistant U.S. Attorney Brian Sullivan asked
Judge Edward C. Reed to delay a final decision in the 1986
class-action lawsuit filed by Nevada Legal Services on behalf of
state residents denied benefits under the loan policy.
   The Health and Human Services Department was named as a third
party in the lawsuit but was not involved in a proposed settlement
between the state and Nevada Legal Services.
   Anticipating the judge's ruling against the federal government in
the case, attorneys for the federal agency requested a 30-day delay
in a final order so they also could work out a settlement.
   The proposed settlement, which must be approved by Reed, was
filed Wednesday.
   In the proposed settlement, Nevada agreed to repay 60 people
$11,767 for welfare payments that were denied when personal loans
were counted as income, making them ineligible for benefits.
   Deputy state Welfare Division Administrator Michael Willden said
he was pleased by the federal government's latest move.
   The Welfare Division had disagreed with the loan-as-income policy
since federal authorities forced it on the states in 1983, he said.
The Aid to Dependent Children program is funded 50 percent by the
federal government.
   ``The loans should have never been counted,'' Willden said. ``But
we had no choice. We would have lost our federal funding. I think
this lawsuit did turn the policy around.
   ``It was clearly shown that the administration's regulations were
violating the welfare laws.''
   Willden said it cost Nevada more than $40,000 to locate people
unqualified for welfare benefits by the loan policy.
   Initial estimates showed as many as 3,000 people in Nevada might
have been affected by the policy, but most could not be found.
   Last year, Reed issued a preliminary injunction preventing the
Welfare Division from counting loans as income in determining
benefit eligibility pending the outcome of the lawsuit.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881203-0039 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-03-88 0850EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-China-SnailFever     12-03 0183</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-China-Snail Fever,0185</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Snail Fever Strikes 1 Million In Southern China</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The blood disease snail fever has been contracted
by 1 million people in southern China and has made a comeback in
some areas where it had previously been wiped out, an official daily
said today.
   The People's Daily said the resurgence of the occasionally fatal
disease occurred because of lax control by local governments and a
drop in funding to eradicate the disease-bearing oncomelania, a
freshwater snail.
   The overseas edition of the daily said the disease has returned
to Shanghai and areas of the southern provinces of Guangdong and
Fujian where it had previously been eliminated.
   Snail fever, also known as schistosomiasis, is prevalent in 12
provinces, and is most serious in riverside or swampy areas of
Hubei, Jiangxi, Anhui and Jiangsu provinces.
   The disease, transmitted into the bloodstream by a parasite,
results in fever, distended stomach, rashes, inflammation of the
liver and in severe cases death. China says it has cured more than
11 million sufferers, or 95 percent of all victims of the disease,
since 1949.
</TEXT>
