<FILEID>AP-NR-12-03-88 0857EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ContraArms     12-03 0732</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Contra Arms,0751</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge to Decide if U.S. Was At War With Nicaragua</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge agreed to decide if
the United States was at war with Nicaragua in the mid-1980s, the
key issue in the case against six men accused of illegally providing
military aid to the Contras.
   In a pretrial hearing Friday, the defendants argued that the
Neutrality Act, under which they were indicted, applies only to
nations with which the nation is at peace, and said the United
States conducted a de facto war against Nicaragua's Sandinista
government. They are asking that the case against them be dismissed.
   U.S. District Judge Norman C. Roettger held the hearing on the
``at-peace'' issue over the objections of the U.S. attorney's
office, which sought to delay the matter until the trial.
   ``It will indeed be an historical decision, whatever the court
determines,'' said defense attorney David Savitz.
   Roettger continued the hearing until Jan. 5, and said he would
decide the issue shortly thereafter.
   The defense Friday presented volumes of Iran-Contra committee and
Tower Commission reports to back up its contention that even during
the periods when Congress halted military aid to the rebels, the
Reagan administration continued to run a war against the Sandinistas.
   Contra leader Adolfo Calero, whose brother Mario Calero is one of
the defendants, took the stand to testify that former National
Security Council aide Oliver North provided the rebels with $32
million during the congressional cutoff, much of which was spent on
arms.
   He said U.S. support actually increased during the 1984-85 period
of the aid cutoff and the defendants' alleged illegal activities.
   ``They told us that the president of the United States would
continue to solicit funds for us,'' sai Adolfo Calero. ``They said
they would continue to support us, and that we should not give up.''
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Eric Debelier tried to draw distinctions
between Nicaragua and other U.S. military actions, including the
Vietnam War, saying that in those cases the executive branch
received congressional support.
   The judge seemed to dismiss that argument, however, mentioning
Korea, Vietnam, the Persian Gulf, Afghanistan and raids on Iran and
Libya.
   ``The only distinction with the Nicaraguan situation is that you
have one branch of government expressing its displeasure,'' Roettger
said.
   Debelier noted that much of the testimony regarding support for
the Contras revolved around commitments made and privately raised
funds provided by North, who is under indictment for his role in
aiding the rebels.
   ``You can't say that because two or three members of the
executive branch are going to solicit funds for the Contras, that is
the same as binding the government'' to warlike activities in
Nicaragua, the prosecutor said.
   The group was indicted in June after charges of Reagan
administration foot-dragging during the highly publicized
investigation. Opponents of aid to the Contras accused Attorney
General Edwin Meese III of stalling the case because it threatened
to uncover illegal activities by North.
   When the indictment _ along with a similar one filed against six
other men accused of running a Contra training camp in the
Everglades _ was finally made public, it accused Contra supporters
of violating the Neutrality Act by launching operations against the
Sandinista government from U.S. soil from October 1984 to March 1985.
   The seven original defentants were Thomas Posey, head of the
Alabama-based Civilian Material Assistance group; Mario Calero, a
former supply manager for the rebels; Joe Adams, Adolfo Calero's
former bodyguard; Jack Terrell, a former mercenary who turned
against the effort and went to authorities; Maco Stewart, a wealthy
former Texas businessman and state official who now lives in France;
Jose Coutin, a Miami Cuban and former CMA liaison in Florida, and
Alex Martinez, a conservative Cuban-American stockbroker.
   The indictment accuses them of recruiting and training
mercenaries to fight with Contras, supplying them with equipment,
leading them on expeditions, including one aimed at blowing up a
Nicaraguan bridge, and violating firearms laws.
   Stewart allegedly financed some of the activities.
   Some of the defendants, including Terrell and Posey, have
produced documents showing the FBI and other agencies were aware of
their activities, and have said that knowledge of their activities
went all the way to the White House.
   Adams pleaded guilty. He was fined $50 and sentenced to a day of
probation. The other six defendants continue to fight the charges.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
