<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Steinberg 1stLd-Writethru a0445 12-03 0563</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Steinberg, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0445,0577</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nussbaum Says Steinberg Admitted Knocking Down Lisa</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf to fix quote; ADDS that trial continues Monday.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY72 of Dec. 2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SAMUEL MAULL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Joel Steinberg admitted knocking his illegally
adopted daughter, Lisa, to the floor on the night prosecutors say he
beat the 6-year-old to death, his former live-in lover testified at
his murder trial.
   ``I knocked her down and she didn't want to get up again. This
staring business (by Lisa) had gotten to be too much,'' Hedda
Nussbaum quoted Steinberg as saying.
   The conversation during a cocaine-smoking session a few hours
after the incident the night of Nov. 1, 1987, Ms. Nussbaum testified
Friday in state court.
   The next morning, Steinberg sounded ``frantic'' as he called for
her, Ms. Nussbaum said. ``And I came running back into the bedroom
and he said, `She stopped breathing.' And he was frantically trying
to revive her.''
   Minutes later, she said, Steinberg told her to call the 911
emergency number and she did. The unconscious girl was taken to a
hospital, where she died three days later of a brain hemorrhage.
   Ms. Nussbaum, 46, is the key prosecution witness against
Steinberg. Her testimony was the first the jury has heard directly
implicating him in the blows that the prosecution says killed the
girl.
   Steinberg, a 47-year-old disbarred lawyer, is charged with
second-degree murder. Ms. Nussbaum was also arrested after Lisa's
death, but charges against her were dropped and she agreed to
testify against him.
   Ms. Nussbaum said Steinberg had angrily accused Lisa of
practicing ``a stare that was supposed to hypnotize the person
stared at.''
   In her second day of testimony, Ms. Nussbaum said she once viewed
Steinberg as ``godlike'' and tried to protect him when he severely
beat and brainwashed her.
   Speaking deliberately, Ms. Nussbaum said she was cut off for
years from her family and friends. During one period, Steinberg
forbade her from leaving their apartment without his permission; she
lost her job as an editor at Random House after repeatedly missing
work because of black eyes, she said.
   ``Most of the time he made me sleep on the floor or in the
bathtub if I had displeased him,'' she testified.
   Asked about her relationship with Steinberg in late 1983 or early
1984, Ms. Nussbaum replied, ``At that time, he began beating me
severely.''
   Prosecutors also submitted as evidence commandments that
Steinberg issued to Ms. Nussbaum that came under the page heading,
``My goals in terms of Joel's interest.''
   He also would force her to write ``punishment lessons'' much like
an errant pupil, writing each item 10 times, Ms. Nussbaum said.
Among the things she was forced to write: ``Anger is destructive,
not constructive.''
   Judge Harold Rothwax instructed the jury that Steinberg was on
trial for the crime he is charged with ``and not for being a
particular kind of person.''
   The judge had agreed to a prosecution argument that the only way
it could explain Ms. Nussbaum was incapable of saving the girl on
the night Lisa was fatally injured was to show the extent to which
she had been dominated by Steinberg.
   Ms. Nussbaum testified Thursday that she didn't call for
emergency help for Lisa because she thought Steinberg had the power
to heal the unconscious girl.
   The trial is scheduled to continue Monday.
</TEXT>
