<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Spain-CrashInquiry     12-03 0256</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Spain-Crash Inquiry,0262</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Report: U.S.-built Spanish Jet Crashed Due To Mechanics' Error</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MADRID, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Faulty installation and assembly of a jet
engine by Spanish air force mechanics caused last month's crash of a
U.S.-built F-18A Hornet fighter-bomber, a newspaper reported today.
   Spain's leading daily El Pais said preliminary results of a
Defense Ministry probe indicated the error caused the twin-engine
jet to crash and burn Nov. 7 in a field near an air base outside the
northern city of Zaragoza.
   The pilot parachuted to safety a minute after takeoff, when an
engine caught fire and an anti-fire instrument failed to put out the
blaze, the paper said, citing unidentified Defense Ministry sources.
   The paper said the sources described the inability of the
anti-fire instrument to extinguish the flames as ``very strange''
and made them think oil, lubricants or some other material kept the
fire alive. Both engines were new and had been recently installed to
replace the original ones.
   A military guard on duty at the Defense Ministry told The
Associated Press today that no one would be available to comment on
the report until Monday.
   The accident provoked criticism of the Socialist administration
of Premier Felipe Gonzalez for buying 72 F-18A Hornets from U.S.
maker McDonnell Douglas for $1.6 billion, the country's largest
single military purchase.
   The investigation involved experts from the Defense Ministry, the
Spanish Air Force, McDonnell Douglas and U.S. jet engine maker
General Electric and was to present its formal findings in the next
few days, the paper said.
</TEXT>
