<DOCNO> AP881203-0043 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-03-88 0957EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Soviet-Reforms     12-03 0662</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Reforms,0681</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reforms Make Effort to Compromise with Republics</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union today published details of its new
government structure that retains central control over the 15
republics while attempting to compromise with their demands for more
autonomy.
   Publication in all major Soviet daily newspapers gave Soviet
citizens their first look at the final version of a political
structure that will govern them beginning in March.
   After an intense five-week public debate in which a quarter
million suggestions were made for changes, the Supreme Soviet, or
parliament, and its Presidium, the country's highest executive body,
approved changes in about half the articles.
   The final project, which President Mikhail S. Gorbachev has said
is crucial to his reform effort, was approved Thursday by the
1,500-member Supreme Soviet with five ``no'' votes.
   The reforms will establish a Congress of People's Deputies,
two-thirds by popular vote and a third by the Communist Party, trade
unions and other organizations. The deputies will pick members of a
smaller two-house Supreme Soviet that will meet twice a year for
four months at a time. The current body meets several days a year.
   The president becomes the head of the the Defense Council and has
the right to conduct international negotiations and sign treaties.
   Among the articles apparently watered down in the final draft was
one that republics opposed because they said it called into question
their right to secede from the Soviet Union.
   The final draft gave the Congress of People's Deputies the power
to ``make decisions on matters of national-state structure which are
in the jurisdiction of the Union of Soviet Socialist Republics.''
   Previous language had given it the power to make decisions ``on
the composition of the U.S.S.R.''
   The new law establishes similar Congresses of People's Deputies
in the 15 republics as well, but leaves it to the republics'
constitutions to outline their powers. The original draft included a
lengthy list of powers of the republics' congresses.
   That also appeared to be an effort to compromise with officials
from the republics, especially Estonia. Estonian President Arnold
Ruutel, in a speech to the Supreme Soviet, said the republic did not
want to be forced to form a Congress of People's Deputies.
   ``It is impossible to find an optimum (political system) for all
regions of the country,'' Ruutel said. ``So we have created our
own.''
   Estonia has led opposition to the constitutional changes. On Nov.
16 its Supreme Soviet made a ``declaration of sovereignty'' in
internal affairs, and proclaimed its right to approve all new
national laws.
   The national government declared the move unconstitutional.
   The final version of the law gives the republics more
representatives in the Soviet of Nationalities, one of the two
houses of the Supreme Soviet, and also ensures they be represented
on a new constitutional oversight commission.
   It orders directives of the central government to be published in
the languages of the republics. But it also gives the national
Presidium specific powers to ensure that the constitutions and laws
of the republics correspond to the national constitution.
   There were complaints that giving organizations such as the
Communist Party and unions the right to elect one-third of the
members of the national Congress would violate the principle of one
man, one vote, by allowing union or party members to vote more than
once, or even hold several seats.
   The final draft says that in selecting the Supreme Soviet, the
Congress of People's Deputies must make sure that members of the
party or other organizations not be over-represented.
   Gorbachev, in a speech Nov. 29, told the Supreme Soviet it would
have the right under the law to veto any order from him or from the
Presidium. Under the new law, however, the presidency still is more
powerful than the largely ceremonial post Gorbachev now holds.
   The new structure goes into effect with the election of the new
Congress of People's Deputies on March 26, 1989.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881203-0044 </DOCNO>
