<HEAD>Mortar Bombs Miss Army Base, Shots Fired at Soldiers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two mortar bombs were fired at a
British army base today but missed their target, police said.
   The two bombs were thought to have been launched from a field
near the Ulster Defense Regiment base, outside Clogher, 50 miles
southwest of Belfast, said a Royal Ulster Constabulary spokesman who
demanded anonymity.
   The constabulary is the British province's police force.
   In a neighboring county, shots were fired during the night at
soldiers on patrol near the town of Balleek on the western border
with the Republic of Ireland, police said. The patrol did not return
fire.
   In Kesh, 80 miles west of Belfast, a bomb exploded in an unmanned
border customs post during the night, causing no injuries but
extensive damage to the small building.
   There were no claims of responsibility for the attacks, but
suspicion fell on the outlawed mainly Roman Catholic Irish
Republican Army.
   The IRA is fighting to oust the British from the mainly
Protestant province and unite it with the predominantly Roman
Catholic republic.
