<HEAD>Second Sailor Dies From Nimitz Accident</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with sailor dying Friday, sted Saturday.
No pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A second sailor has died of injuries
sustained in an explosion and fire on the aircraft carrier USS
Nimitz, officials said today.
   Chadwick R. Henderson, 19, of Rockford, Ill., was in intensive
care at a U.S. military hospital when he died Friday night from
extensive burns he suffered in the accident Wednesday, said Marie
Shaw, spokeswoman at the Landstuhl Army Regional Medical Center.
   The Landstuhl facility, 70 miles southwest of Frankfurt, is
equipped with a special burn unit. Family members had flown to West
Germany and were at the hospital when Henderson died, Mrs. Shaw said.
   The Nimitz was operating in the northern Arabian Sea when a 20mm
nose gun on an A-7E Corsair fighter-bomber fired inadvertently
during maintenance, touching off an explosion and fire that damaged
seven aircraft.
   Scott Dimberg, 23, of Redfield, S.D., died aboard the carrier and
Henderson suffered second- and third-degree burns in the fire.
   Emergency deck crewmen were able to contain the blaze within 20
minutes, and no damage was sustained by the 90,944-ton carrier, the
military said.
</TEXT>
