<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Carlucci 2ndLd-Writethru a0469 12-03 0388</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Carlucci, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0469,0394</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pentagon Chief Arrives In Oman</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 7th graf, ``Carlucci also...'' to CORRECT that second
sailor died Friday nite, sted Saturday. Pickup 8th graf pvs, ``Seven
aircraft...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD PYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defense Secretary Frank C. Carlucci
arrived in Oman today to begin a four-day tour including visits to
Navy warships and stops in three other Persian Gulf countries.
   Carlucci was quoted by the official Omani News Agency as saying
his trip was to reaffirm the Reagan administration's interest in
continuing strong ties with Oman and ``renewing the commitment for
stability in the region.''
   Oman, on the far eastern end of the Persian Gulf, is one of the
four Arab states that has provided the United States with limited
support facilities for its naval operations in the waterway.
   The arrangements are a particularly sensitive matter in Oman,
which shares control of the strategic Strait of Hormuz with Iran and
has the closest ties of any gulf Arab state with Tehran.
   The Omanis permit the U.S. Navy to refuel warships at a base on
the Arabian Sea and have access to other facilities that U.S.
officials refuse to discuss.
   Carlucci, after attending a meeting of NATO defense ministers in
Belgium, flew to Muscat for a two-day visit at the invitation of
Oman's Defense Minister, Mutassim Bin Hamoud Busaidi. He was
accompanied by Assistant Defense Secretary Richard Armitage and
several other officials.
   Carlucci also was to visit the aircraft carrier USS Nimitz,
operating in the Arabian Sea off Oman. On Wednesday, an explosion
and fire aboard the huge carrier killed one sailor. A second sailor,
who was seriously wounded, died Friday night in a U.S. military
hospital in West Germany, officials said.
   Seven aircraft were damaged in the accident, which occurred when
a 20mm nose gun on a Corsair fighter-bomber fired inadvertently
during maintenance, the Navy said. It hit a KA6-D Intruder tanker
plane loaded with aviation fuel.
   After Oman, Carlucci was to fly to Bahrain, Saudi Arabia and
Kuwait to meet with top officials, probably for the last time before
the Reagan administration leaves office in January. He was due back
in Washington on Wednesday.
   President-elect George Bush has said he will name his own man to
replace Carlucci, who assumed the Pentagon post about a year ago.
</TEXT>
