<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Big Catch,0153</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Inspector Makes Unexpected Catch</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LYON, France (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A police inspector who took the day off to go
fishing Saturday caught a real whopper _ a sack of stolen jewels
weighing about two pounds, police sources said.
   The officer, who was not named, was fishing on the Rhone River
near the village of Pierre-Benite, a suburb of Lyon, when his line
caught something he believed was dinner.
   Reeling it in, he found a bag hung on the line containing
necklaces and rings of precious stones and bracelets of lesser
value, police said, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   Police speculated that thieves had selected the most valuable
pieces and tossed the rest in the river. They said the difference in
the value of the jewels indicated they had come from different
robberies.
   They did not provide a value for the jewels or other details.
</TEXT>
