<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Brites     12-03 0563</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brites,0585</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bright & Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Looking for something fashionable yet practical
for the woman who lives a life of danger?
   Give her bullet-resistant furs, in a wide variety of styles.
   The furs are lined with Kevlar, a synthetic fiber that is five
times stronger than its weight in steel and is used in bullet-proof
vests worn by police.
   ``I see the full fur coats being worn by movie stars, actresses,
Ivana Trump-types, Barbara Bush, maybe even Imelda Marcos,'' said
Stephen D'Andrilli, president of Guardian Group International, and a
distributor of Kevlar.
   As he spoke, a Joan Collins look-alike swept into the showroom of
Jiuliana Originals Inc. in a full-length $80,000 Russian sable coat.
Another model followed in a three-quarter-length $8,500 fox jacket
of light brown and white-flecked fur.
   ``A Madonna-rock-star-type would wear a coat like this,'' said
furrier Thomas F. Zizzo. He and his mother, Jiuliana Zizzo, designed
the coats.
   A woman in jeans modeled a butter-soft black leather bomber
jacket lined with reversible black mink and Kevlar, which retails
for $5,500.
   ``We don't want someone to buy a coat they wouldn't want to
wear,'' Zizzo said. ``They can wear these coats every day, so they
can utilize the protection.''
   ``We can do anything,'' Zizzo said. ``If Imelda Marcos wanted
shoes, we could do bullet-resistant shoes for her.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>KENNEWICK, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Col. Sherman Potter, stylish Cpl. Max
Klinger and most of the other characters from ``M.A.S.H.'' showed up
at Kennewick General Hospital.
   It wasn't Alan Alda and company, but hospital employees poking
fun at their working conditions.
   A remodeling project has the place resembling an Army field
hospital, with portable lights along hallways and plywood walls and
ceilings in areas, so the staff decided to come to work Friday
attired to match their surroundings.
   In addition to looking the part, employees were served military
food, including creamed chipped beef on toast, said Darlene Smolen,
hospital marketing director.
   ``All the construction is very stressful, but laughter is the
best medicine,'' she said. ``We turned it into something fun, and it
really did a lot to build morale here.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   State employees on the top half of the
20-story Sillers Building freeze in the morning. In the afternoon,
they swelter.
   And opening the windows? Well, that's another story.
   ``When it gets cold, it's hard to sit at your desk. We keep the
coffee pots going eight hours a day up here. The secretaries have
these heavy coats on at their typewriters,'' said Liz Cleveland,
whose office is on the 13th floor.
   It's been about two months since the demise of the fans that run
the heating and cooling system at the top of one of downtown
Jackson's tallest buildings.
   While it's cold in the mornings, sunlight streaming through the
windows causes the temperature to soar during the day.
   ``What we've been doing is prying open the windows in the
afternoon, but on the 13th floor, it's like sitting in the cockpit
of a helicopter,'' said Cleveland, manager of the state Department
of Economic Development's export-import office. ``One day my door
blew shut and all the ceiling tiles blew out of my office.''
   New fans had to be specially ordered, so the top floors probably
won't be comfortable until after the Christmas holidays, said George
A. Jones III, director of the Bureau of Capitol Facilities.
</TEXT>
