<1ST_LINE>r i AM-China-Pollution     12-03 0459</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-China-Pollution,0477</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pollution Ravages China, Cleanup Costs Increasing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN POMFRET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China's breakneck economic development is
endangering the country's environment and saddling society with a
huge cleanup bill, the leading paper said Saturday.
   The People's Daily reported that ``if forceful policies are not
implemented,'' the nation faces a future of denuded forests, dirty
lakes, barren grasslands and smoggy skies.
   The report said the twin evils of pollution and misuse of natural
resources have reached such a state in China that annual cleanup
costs are estimated at about $23 billion.
   ``By the end of the century,'' the paper said, ``if the
environment continues to worsen, it will become a major factor
limiting economic development.''
   The paper said about 1 percent of the country's $270 billion
gross national product _ or $2.7 billion _ should be devoted each
year to ecology.
   But the Xinhua news agency reported that by October only $1.8
billion had been allocated for the purpose, although it said the
state planned an increase of 50 percent in coming years.
   Since 1978, China's gross national product has jumped 100
percent, but the economic and industrial growth has come at an
enormous ecological cost _ one which the government has only
recently begun to realize.
   A Xinhua report said that by the year 2000, nearly half of
China's 2,800 lakes could be polluted. An earlier survey on 58,900
miles of rivers found that 20 percent were polluted and another 8
percent seriously contaminated.
   Reports have blamed acid rain, caused by burning the high-sulfur
coal that predominates in China, for killing trees in Hangzhou, a
beautiful lakeside metropolis south of Shanghai.
   In the countryside, increased use of chemical fertilizers has
seriously affected soil quality and water resources. In addition,
``timber poachers,'' who raid forests for firewood and building
materials, have been fingered in the country's continuing problem
with deforestation.
   The People's Daily said Saturday's report was based on a
four-year study to forecast environmental conditions in the year
2000.
   The report said that even if ``forceful policies'' were adopted,
China would only be able to treat 53 percent of its liquid waste by
the turn of the century. It now treats only about 20 percent of the
waste.
   In addition, the study predicted acid rain would continue to
plague highly industrialized areas and the output of solid waste
would more than double by 2000.
   The report said that damage to farmland accounted for the lion's
share of the annual financial cleanup cost, demanding about $9.7
billion dollars a year. Water pollution came next, accounting for
$4.2 billion in damage annually.
   Third came the financial loss from denuded forests, followed by
air pollution, problems caused by chemical fertilizers and the
destruction of water resources.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881203-0053 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-03-88 1120EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--SaltPanic     12-03 0181</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Salt Panic,0188</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Panic Buying of Salt Hits Canton</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Panic buying of salt hit China's southern city
of Canton, sending its prices soaring in some privately run food
stores, a pro-Beijing newspaper reported Saturday.
   The Chinese-language New Evening Post said the price rises
violated regulations and the merchants would be held responsible.
The report did not elaborate.
   Rumors that vouchers would be needed to buy salt resulted in long
customer lines outside several food stores in Canton recently, the
newspaper said.
   Canton is about 90 miles west of this British colony.
   The price of salt rose from 10 cents to 35 cents at the stores,
the newspaper reported without giving the unit of measure of the
salt.
   Provincial and city governments said warehouses were stocked and
no voucher program existed, the newspaper reported.
   China's economic reform policy has been slowed by inflation that
has soared to a post-1950s high of more than 26 percent.
   There have been recent reports of panic buying of textiles in
Shanghai and salt in 19 areas, where authorities immediately imposed
rations.
