<1ST_LINE>r i PM-AfghanTalks     12-03 0413</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Afghan Talks,0424</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviets and Afghan Rebels Meet</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ABDULLAH AL-SHEHRI</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RIYADH, Saudi Arabia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet officials and Afghan
guerrillas today began informal talks on prisoners of war, the
future relationship between Afghanistan and Moscow and the future of
the Soviet-backed Kabul government.
   The face-to-face talks in Taif, a Saudi Arabian resort 600 miles
from Riyadh, were the first between the Soviets and a seven-group
guerrilla alliance since the 1979 Soviet invasion of Afghanistan.
The Soviets have met other rebel groups on two occasions earlier
this year.
   Formal negotiations were expected to begin later today or Sunday,
sources close to the talks said.
   Saudi Arabia was chosen as a venue by the Afghan resistance
groups because of the influence it wields in the Islamic world.
   The kingdom has said repeatedly it would consider establishing
ties with Moscow only after Soviet troops complete their withdrawal
from Afghanistan. The Soviets intervened there in December 1979.
   The head of the Soviet delegation was Yuli Vorontsov, a deputy
foreign minister who recently was named ambassador to Afghanistan,
the sources said on condition of anonymity.
   Burhanuddin Rabbani, leader of the loose alliance of Afghan
resistance groups based in Peshawar, Pakistan, has been in the
kingdom for two weeks. Other rebel leaders were expected to join the
official talks later.
   Vorontsov is the second Soviet official to visit Saudi Arabia in
less than a year. Vladimir Polyakov, another deputy foreign
minister, came in February in what was seen then as a move toward
rapprochement between the two countrues.
   Rabbani has stressed that the overriding focus for the rebels
during the talks will be on complete withdrawal of Soviet troops
from Afghanistan.
   More than half of the 100,000 troops have left since Moscow and
Pakistan signed a U.N.-sponsored accord in April calling for
withdrawal.
   The rest of the troops were supposed to be out by Feb. 15, but
the Soviets recently halted the withdrawal to protest what they
called continued funding of the guerrillas by Pakistan and the
United States.
   Moscow and the Marxist government of President Najib are now
seeking to convene an international conference to demilitarize
Afghanistan and set up a coalition government with the rebels.
   Vladimir Petrovsky, also a Soviet deputy foreign minister, told
reporters in Moscow on Friday that the Vorontsov-Rabbani meeting was
arranged by the Saudi government with the cooperation of the Afghan
government.
   He said no representatives of Najib's government or Pakistan, the
main backer of the rebels, will attend the meeting.
</TEXT>
