<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel,0299</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Troops Kill Teen-ager During Clashes In Occupied Areas</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli troops shot and killed a Palestinian boy
and wounded 20 Arabs today as stone-throwing rioters clashed with
soldiers in the occupied territories, Arab reports and hospital
officials said.
   An army spokeswoman confirmed the death and said several
Palestinians were wounded. She said she could not give an exact
number of wounded.
   In response to the unrest, the army clamped curfews on three West
Bank towns and barred reporters from entering Nablus which, with
100,000 Arab residents, is the West Bank's largest city.
   The 16-year-old boy was killed in Nablus when troops opened fire
on demonstrators who erected barricades and hurled rocks and bottles
at soldiers, the army said. Arab reports said the boy was taken to
the city's Ittihad Hospital after he was shot in the neck and chest.
   The youth's death raised to at least 318 the number of Arabs
killed since the start of the yearlong Palestinian uprising against
Israel's military occupation of the West Bank and Gaza Strip. Eleven
Israelis also have died.
   A 27-year-old man was shot in the head with a plastic bullet in
Nablus and taken to Ramallah Hospital where he was in critical
condition, a hospital official said.
   In the Gaza Strip, Arab witnesses said troops shot and wounded at
least five youths when nearly 100 demonstrators threw rocks at cars
and soldiers outside a Palestinian elementary school. The army said
it was checking the report.
   Witnesses said soldiers opened fire with rubber bullets and live
ammunition when stone-throwing youths outside the school in Khan
Yunis refused to disperse. The youngest of the wounded was an
11-year-old boy shot in the right leg with a plastic bullet, Arab
reports said.
