<2ND_LINE>AM-PTL Grand Jury,0304</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Grand Jury May Hand Up PTL Indictments Next Week, Sources Say</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The federal grand jury investigating Jim
Bakker and former associates at PTL may return indictments this
week, a newspaper reported Saturday.
   Unidentified sources told The Charlotte Observer on Friday that
they believe prosecutors are ready to end the 17-month investigation
and intend to present an indictment for the grand jury to consider.
   ``I would guess they're going to come back with an indictment
next week. I don't know what day,'' a source told The Observer.
   Bakker's attorney, Jim Toms, who has met with prosecutors, said
he believes Bakker will be charged with mail and wire fraud
involving PTL ``lifetime partnerships'' and with tax violations in
connection with PTL money spent on Bakker.
   Lifetime partners received free lodging at PTL's Christian theme
park in Fort Mill, S.C., in exchange for big contributions to the
evangelical empire built by Jim and Tammy Bakker before his downfall
in a sex and money scandal in 1987.
   Prosecutors have reserved a courtroom for Monday through
Wednesday for the grand jury to meet. Toms and other sources said
they believe prosecutors on Monday will explain what charges they
believe ought to be brought.
   U.S. Attorney Tom Ashcraft refused to discuss the secret
proceedings.
   Last month, Bakker, former PTL executive Richard Dortch and Roe
Messner, PTL's former chief builder, received letters from
prosecutors informing them that they are targets of the
investigation and inviting them to testify.
   Only Messner, a Wichita, Kan., contractor, accepted. He refused
to talk with reporters after testifying Wednesday and Thursday.
   Bakker resigned from PTL in a scandal over the payment of hush
money to Jessica Hahn, with whom he had a sexual encounter in a
hotel room in 1980.
