<1ST_LINE>u w AM-HomelessAid Bjt   12-03 0684</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Homeless Aid, Bjt,650</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>For Release 6:30 p.m. EST; time set by source</NOTE>
<HEAD>Congressman Complains Social Security Refusing To Spend Money For
Homeless</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Social Security Administration has bottled
up money to be spent on the homeless at the same time the agency's
head is considering spending some $1.6 million on souvenir
certificates, a congressman complained.
   The attack leveled by Rep. Ted Weiss, D-N.Y., at Social Security
Commissioner Dorcas Hardy comes at a time she is quietly campaigning
for a post in the administration of President-elect George Bush.
   However, Weiss, chairman of the House Government Operations
subcommittee on human resources, denied that his criticism _
contained in a letter to Bush _ was designed to derail Hardy's
career.
   He urged Bush to ``reject the misplaced priorities'' of Hardy.
   Weiss said he and his subcommittee have had differences with
Hardy on other matters ``at a time when there was never any question
about her continuation in office.''
   Meanwhile, on a different matter, Hardy announced Saturday that
she has rejected a controversial draft proposal to narrow disability
applicants' appeal rights.
   She said she remains convinced that the disability appeals
process needs reforms, but said the low-level staff proposal _ which
was leaked to a newspaper two weeks ago before reaching her desk _
was not equitable, compassionate or efficient.
   Weiss said Hardy has not acted on part of a 1987 budget act
authorizing $1.25 million last year and $2.5 million this year in
grants for homeless outreach projects.
   Hardy has argued that Congress failed to provide money for the
program and that it duplicated other government services.
   She recommended that the Department of Health and Human Services
seek repeal of the program or find an agency more familiar with
state grant programs to run it.
   Congress wanted states to use the money to find and help homeless
people eligible for benefits, particularly the mentally and
physically disabled who are entitled to Supplemental Security
Income, Weiss said in the Dec. 2 letter.
   ``It's really the season that warrants it,'' he said in an
interview. ``Here we are with winter upon us. There are people out
on the streets who are obviously and clearly qualified for SSI
benefits. The purpose of the legislation was to help states reach
out and identify those individuals. ... We felt we ought to bring it
to the attention of the president-elect.''
   Phil Gambino, a spokesman for the Social Security Administration,
said Congress not only failed to allocate money for the outreach
grant program but in fact gave the agency less money in its overall
budget than it requested for fiscal 1988 and 1989.
   ``Therefore we have to rely on other alternative means'' to reach
the homeless, Gambino said. He said employees at the 1,300 SSA
offices nationwide work closely with shelters and advocacy groups to
make sure the homeless receive benefits.
   ``Commissioner Hardy is very much concerned that we deliver our
services compassionately and fairly to the homeless. We think we're
doing a good job of it,'' Gambino said.
   Weiss called that claim ``baloney. ... They're not doing any kind
of outreach that I can see. Obviously it was the congressional view
that the kind of work that was needed was not being done.''
   He said there was no specific allocation because Congress assumed
the agency would fund the relatively tiny grant program from its
general budget.
   At the same time she was fighting the homeless program, Weiss
said, Hardy was supporting a $1.6 million plan to send decorative
certificates, suitable for framing, to Social Security
beneficiaries. Hardy approved the plan despite a recommendation to
scrap it, according to documents supplied by Weiss' office.
   ``It's a nutty idea,'' Weiss said. ``It contrasts what she thinks
money ought to be spent for as opposed to what the real needs of
people are.''
   Gambino said Hardy still thinks the certificates are a good idea
but they haven't been instituted. ``We haven't killed the proposal,
but it is not a high priority at this time based on its cost and our
funding situation,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881203-0060 </DOCNO>
