<HEAD>Seventy-Seven Arrested in Ohio</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police on Saturday arrested 77 anti-abortion
protesters for blocking a clinic while singing Christmas carols and
hymns.
   About 100 other people marched on the sidewalk in front of
Planned Parenthood's Elizabeth Campbell Center, carrying signs that
read ``Rescue in progress'' and ``Warning: Killing babies may be
hazardous to your soul.''
   Officers escorted most of those arrested to police vans but had
to carry three protesters, who will face resisting arrest charges,
said Police Chief Lawrence Whalen.
   All 77 demonstrators were booked on trespassing charges at the
Hamilton County jail.
   Two busloads of officers arrived to make the arrests and blocked
off the street in front of the clinic.
   ``With the streets being blocked off, the girls can't get in
there. They've got another day to think about it,'' said Sara Meyer,
spokeswoman for the Rescue Cincinnati group coordinating the protest.
   Ann Mitchell, executive director of Planned Parenthood in
Cincinnati, said no patients canceled appointments. She said the
protest was anticipated and patients were scheduled for appointments
later than usual.
