<FILEID>AP-NR-12-03-88 1229EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-TerroristTrap     12-03 0444</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Terrorist Trap,0456</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviet Exile And American Entrepeneur Build Terrorist Trap</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN GALVIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An exiled Soviet engineer and an American security
consultant say they are nearly ready to market an anti-terrorism
system designed to halt gate crashers with their own horsepower.
   ``It is quite an old Indian trap idea,'' said Alexander Gorlov,
professor of mechanical engineering at Northeastern University and
chief designer of the Terrorist Vehicle Arresting System, which can
demolish a 15,000-pound truck traveling at 50 mph.
   The trap consists of two cables and a net stretched across an
entryway. If an intruder tries to drive through, the tension on the
net and cables rotates a 1,500-pound, spiked turnstile that slams
into the side of the vehicle, forcing it against a barrier.
   After the 1986 terrorist attack that claimed the lives of 241
Marines in Beirut, security officials recognized the need for a more
reliable defense against car bomb attacks.
   Steel barricades that rise from the ground to stop intruders in
their tracks have been installed at the entrances of the Capitol,
the White House and many other government buildings in the United
States and abroad.
   Ed Newell, a Boston resident who worked as a law enforcement
consultant much of his 77 years, said those 1,500-pound barricades
are difficult to maintain.
   ``You've got to raise and lower that mass for every vehicle that
comes and goes all day long, every day, waiting for 10 years for
some guy to crash,'' Newell said. ``People walk by and they see this
thing standing there and it makes them think that these people
(inside) have a bunker mentality.''
   In the system developed by Gorlov and Newell, only the 150-pound
cables and nylon net that hang a foot off the ground need to be
raised and lowered. The cables slide into a groove in the ground at
the flip of a switch to admit authorized vehicles and can be
returned to position in one second.
   The turnstile stands at the side of the road, swinging into
action only when a gate crasher drags on the net.
   Gorlov and Newell have some testing to complete. ``But now we've
developed all the details and, practically speaking, we're ready for
mass production,'' Gorlov said.
   They said believe they can sell the recently patented system for
between $15,000 and $25,000.
   Gorlov, 56, and his wife, Ella, formerly professors at Moscow
universities, were banished from the Soviet Union 13 years ago and
settled in Brookline.
   He said he was exlied because of his friendship with Nobel
laureate Alexander Solzhenitzsyn, who chronicled Gorlov's brush with
the KGB in his novel ``The Oak and the Calf.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881203-0067 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-03-88 1231EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Reforms     12-03 0618</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Reforms,0639</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reforms Keep Tight Rein on Republics, Restructure Center</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet citizens got their first look Saturday at
the fine points of a new political system that keeps a tight rein on
the 15 republics, strengthens the presidency and builds a more
dynamic parliament.
   Major daily Soviet newspapers published details of the reforms,
which were approved Thursday by the Supreme Soviet parliament and
will go into effect with elections next March 26.
   The reforms, adopted after five weeks of intense public debate,
attempt to forge a compromise between demands by the republics for
autonomy and the need for central control by the government in
Moscow.
   But a lawyer for a grass-roots Lithuanian movement scoffed at
compromises made to the restive republics and said his organization
was writing a complaint over President Mikhail S. Gorbachev's
reforms that will arrive at the United Nations about the same time
the Soviet leader does.
   ``All the things that choked and are choking us are still
there,'' Kazimieras Motieka, a member of the governing council of
the Sajudis movement, said in a telephone interview from the
Lithuanian capital of Vilnius.
   The new system establishes a 2,250-member Congress of People's
Deputies that will include for the first time members of the
Communist Party, trade union and other organizations as well as
representatives chosen on the basis of geographical districts and
ethnic homelands.
   The congress will choose a smaller, more active Supreme Soviet
that is to meet eight months instead of several days a year.
   Several of the 15 republics, especially the Baltic republics of
Lithuanian, Latvia and Estonia, have complained that the laws as
proposed by Gorbachev in October concentrated too much power in
Moscow.
   Motieka said the new laws give the national parliament wide power
over the economy in the republics. By including property under the
jurisdication of the national Supreme Soviet, Moscow established
``that what is in our republic is not our property,'' he said.
   ``We can't organize our own agriculture,'' he said. ``We can't
even change wages.''
   Among the articles changed in the final draft of the reform was
one opposed by republics because they said it called into question
their right to secede from the Soviet Union.
   The final version gave the Congress of People's Deputies power to
``make decisions on matters of national-state structure which are in
the jurisdiction of the Union of Soviet Socialist Republics.''
   Previous language had given it the power to make decisions ``on
the composition of the U.S.S.R.''
   The language appeared weaker, but Motieka contended that the
change was in words only.
   Estonia has led opposition to the constitutional changes. On Nov.
16 its Supreme Soviet made a ``declaration of sovereignty'' in
internal affairs and proclaimed its right to approve all new
national laws.
   The national government declared that move unconstitutional, but
the Estonian parliament meets Monday to discuss further expressions
of autonomy.
   The final version of the law gives republics more representatives
in one of the two houses of the Supreme Soviet and representation on
a new constitutional oversight commission.
   It orders directives of the central government to be published in
the languages of the republics.
   But it also gives the national Presidium specific powers to
ensure that the constitutions and laws of the republics correspond
to the national constitution.
   Gorbachev leaves Monday for New York, where he will address the
United Nations and meet with President Reagan and President-elect
George Bush. He then travels to Cuba and Britain.
   Motieka said the governing council of Sajudis agreed during a
session Saturday to send a complaint to the United Nations. A draft
was being written and a vote would be taken Sunday, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881203-0068 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-03-88 1236EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Bush-Gorbachev Bjt   12-03 0903</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush-Gorbachev, Bjt,890</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush-Gorbachev Meetings Go Back To 1985</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERENCE HUNT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP White House Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush has sized up Mikhail Gorbachev
during nearly two hours of meetings in Moscow and Washington and
concludes that the Soviet leader is tough, self-confident and
outgoing _ ``a new and more enlightened'' leader.
   At the same time there is nothing in Bush's recent marks to
contradict his year-old assessment that Gorbachev also ``is no
freedom-loving friend of democracy.''
   In contrast to President Reagan's newfound optimism about the
Soviet Union and its leadership, Bush had taken a more cautious
approach. ``The cold war is not over,'' Bush said earlier this year,
even as he praised Gorbachev's reforms as revolutionary.
   From his personal experience, Bush knows Gorbachev can be a real
crowd pleaser _ in Bush's words, ``a Western-style communicator.''
   During the superpower summit last December, Bush was along for
the ride in Gorbachev's limousine when the Soviet leader abruptly
ordered his driver to halt, jumped out of the car and plunged into a
noontime crowd in downtown Washington.
   The campaign-style stop delighted onlookers who rushed to greet
Gorbachev. Bush, then a candidate, shared Gorbachev's limelight,
joining him on the street to shake hands and wave.
   On Wednesday, Bush will fly to New York to accompany Reagan at a
meeting with Gorbachev on Governors Island in New York Harbor.
   Although Bush will be the man Gorbachev will have to deal with
after Jan. 20, the vice president promises he'll play a back seat
role to Reagan in New York.
   ``It will be President Reagan's meeting,'' Bush says. ``I'll be
there as vice president of the United States and I expect they'll be
aware they're talking to the next president.''
   Colin Powell, the White House national security adviser, said the
Soviets understand that Bush's role will be secondary to Reagan's
and that ``it would not be appropriate then for the vice president
to have a separate agenda.''
   Even so, the meeting provides an important opportunity for a
smooth transition in superpower relations.
   Bush was the first American leader to meet with Gorbachev after
he became head of the Soviet government.
   As Reagan's emissary, Bush went to Moscow in March, 1985, for the
funeral of Soviet leader Konstantin Chernenko. At the conclusion of
that trip, Bush met with the newly named Soviet leader: Gorbachev.
   The meeting lasted 85 minutes and Bush described their
discussions as ``useful'' and ``constructive.''
   Bush and Gorbachev saw each other again during the Washington
summit. Bush was present in each of the plenary sessions during the
three days of talks between Gorbachev and Reagan.
   During that summit, Bush also had a private, 23-minute meeting
with Gorbachev at the Soviet Embassy in Washington before the two
men attended breakfast with other guests. It was after that
breakfast meeting that Bush and Gorbachev rode together to the White
House and made the impromptu stop.
   At the end of the summit, when Gorbachev went to Andrews Air
Force Base to depart Washington, Bush again was in the limousine
with the Soviet leader.
   Reflecting on the summit, Bush said Gorbachev was ``an impressive
man _ self-confident, gregarious and obviously intelligent. He is
forthright and direct and he has a sense of humor and a Western
style that makes him different from his predecessors.
   ``But make no mistake about it, this is no freedom-loving friend
of democracy,'' Bush said last December. ``He is an orthodox,
committed Marxist and a formidable and determined competitor for
world power.''
   Bush has praised Gorbachev's move toward reforms, saying, ``I am
impressed by the steps he has taken for more openness, more
reform.'' However, Bush usually couples his praise with a statement
that the Soviet Union will be judged ultimately by what its actions
on arms reductions, human rights, and regional tensions.
   In some recent speeches, Bush has struck a more conciliatory tone
toward Gorbachev.
   In an address a month before the presidential election, Bush said
Gorbachev and his foreign minister, Eduard Shevardnadze, were tough
but represented ``a new and more enlightened generation of Soviet
leaders in the Kremlin _ much better able to communicate with the
West, more committed to openness and internal reform.''
   ``This offers promise but in no way should lessen our commitment
to peace through strength _ a policy we must continue,'' said Bush
   In another speech a day later, Bush again referred to Gorbachev
and Shevardnadze and said: ``They are serious people. They know they
must change. After 70 years of the Marxist-Leninist state, it's
pretty hard to explain to the Soviet people why they don't have
either bread or freedom, why the food situation is worse than it was
a decade ago, or why life expectancy has dropped.''
   Bush said Gorbachev ``is clearly a different kind of Soviet
leader than we have seen recently. He is prepared to take radical
steps. He is able to reverse course when Soviet policies fail, when
the costs become too high.''
   A week before he was elected, Bush said that should he become
president, he would be prepared to meet with Gorbachev ``at the
earliest time that would serve the interests of world peace.''
   He said he would want to engage in ``a serious and direct
examination of where we are and how we can best go forward toward
further arms reductions, a decrease in regional tensions and further
adherence to human rights and thus toward a surer peace.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
