<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Gulf-Carlucci     12-03 0535</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gulf-Carlucci,0550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pentagon Chief On His Last Visit To Persian Gulf</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD PYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defense Secretary Frank C. Carlucci met
with defense officials in Oman on Saturday at the start of a
four-day Persian Gulf tour expected to be the last to the region by
a top Reagan administration official.
   Carlucci was quoted by the official Omani News Agency as saying
his trip was aimed at ``renewing the (American) commitment for
stability in the region'' in the aftermath of the 8-year-old
Iran-Iraq war.
   He was to visit Bahrain, Saudi Arabia and Kuwait and go aboard
several U.S. Navy warships before returning to Washington on Dec. 7,
U.S. officials said.
   They said a flight deck explosion and fire aboard the aircraft
carrier USS Nimitz four days ago was not likely to deter plans for
Carlucci to visit that ship, which is operating in the north Arabian
Sea off Oman. The accident killed two sailors.
   Navy investigators were trying to determine why a gun on an A-7E
Corsair fighter-bomber accidentally fired during an overhaul. The
gunburst hit a parked KA6-D Intruder tanker plane loaded with 4,000
gallons of aviation fuel and touched off a fire that damaged seven
aircraft.
   The Arab states on Carlucci's itinerary have provided support for
the U.S. effort to protect commercial shipping during the gulf war,
which ended in a U.N.-sponsored cease-fire Aug. 20.
   The Omanis allow U.S. Navy warships to refuel at a base on the
Arabian Sea and to have access to other facilities.
   The arrangements are a particularly sensitive matter in Oman,
which shares with Iran the control of the Strait of Hormuz, the
entrance to the gulf, and has maintained the closest ties of any
gulf state with Tehran during the war.
   Carlucci flew to Muscat, the Omani capital, accompanied by
Assistant Defense Secretary of Defense Richard Armitage and other
officials.
   On Saturday, the Pentagon chief met with Oman's defense minister,
deputy prime minister for security and defense, foreign affairs
minister and deputy prime minister for legal affairs, the official
news agency said.
   Senior U.S. officials and diplomats contend that Washington's
relations with Arab states in the Persian Gulf are the best ever as
a result of the American effort to protect shipping.
   President-elect George Bush has said he will choose his own man
to replace Carlucci, but he is expected to maintain the Reagan
administration's stated policy of scaling back U.S. forces if the
Iraq-Iran truce holds up.
   The U.S. fleet already has been trimmed by two ships since the
cease-fire, to 25 at present _ by far the largest naval force in the
region.
   The number of fleets in the gulf will be down to four by year's
end as the Netherlands and Italy pull out. The remaining fleets are
from Britain, France and the Soviet Union.
   U.S. sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, said Carlucci
was to visit the Nimitz, the flagship USS La Salle, the missile
cruiser USS Josephus Daniels and perhaps one of the six gulf-based
U.S. minesweepers.
   The Navy ended direct escorting of U.S.-flagged Kuwaiti tankers
two months ago, but still monitors the vessels along the 550-mile
route between Kuwait and the Strait of Hormuz.
</TEXT>
