<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Poland     12-03 0325</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Poland,0333</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Walesa Told He May Travel to France</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Solidarity leader Lech Walesa, who has not
been allowed to leave Poland since 1981, has been given permission
to travel to France later this month, his wife said Saturday.
   The change in policy will allow him to attend a ceremony in Paris
on Dec. 10 marking the 40th anniversary of the Universal Declaration
of Human Rights.
   Walesa, who was invited by French President Francois Mitterrand,
applied for a passport last week and was informed on Saturday that
he may pick it up Monday, said Danuta Walesa, speaking from the
couple's home in Gdansk.
   Mrs. Walesa said Walesa was suffering from a flu and cold and was
unable to come to the telephone.
   ``He has gotten a passport. Someone called from the passport
office and said he can come and pick it up on Monday,'' she said.
``He's happy that he's going to France and will breathe some
different air.'' Mrs. Walesa said she would remain in Poland and
take care of the couple's eight children.
   An aide, Piotr Konopka, said Walesa would work his travel plans
out soon and decide whether to take along other members of the
banned Solidarity union.
   Foreign Minister Tadeusz Olechowski was due to return Sunday from
an official visit to France. Asked about Walesa's passport
application earlier in the week, he had said he expected it to be
issued.
   The trip would be the first time the 1983 Noble Peace Prize
winner received permission to leave Poland since the imposition of
martial law at the end of 1981. Walesa had visited Paris in October
of that year.
   Polish citizens must apply for a passport whenever they wish to
travel to a non-socialist country. Travel restrictions have been
eased in recent years, although some passports are still denied for
political reasons.
   In March, the government denied Walesa permission to attend an
international trade union conference in Australia.
</TEXT>
