<FILEID>AP-NR-12-03-88 1259EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w PM-US-Soviet 1stLdWritethru a0804 12-03 0520</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US-Soviet, 1st Ld Writethru, a0804,510</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 9 grafs new with radio address, picks up 3rd graf pvs, The
Reykjavik</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan said today he feels nostalgic
as he faces his last session with Soviet leader Mikhail S.
Gorbachev, and will use the meeting to introduce his successor as a
man who represents ``change, yes, but also continuity.''
   Reagan, in his weekly rado address delivered from Camp David,
Md., said he was looking forward to the upcoming meeting and
luncheon on Wednesday, set on Governors Island in New York City.
   The president recalled that since he first met the Soviet leader
in Geneva in 1985, the U.S.-Soviet relationship has developed and
resulted in the first agreement to get rid of an entire class of
nuclear weapons.
   ``This will be our last such meeting, and I must admit that I
would not have predicted after first taking office, that some day I
would be waxing nostalgic about my meetings with Soviet leaders,''
Reagan said, in a reference to his days as an ardent anti-communist.
``But here we are, for the fifth time, Mr. Gorbachev and I together,
in the hope of furthering peace.''
   Reagan pointed out that despite their agreement on arms control,
there is much work to be done over differences on that subject, and
on human rights, regional problems, and in bilateral relations.
   The goal of improved U.S.-Sviet relations ``must continue byond
any single presidency or term of office,'' Reagan said, adding that
he is ``particularly delighted'' that President-elect George Bush
will join the meeting.
   ``No one is better versed in the details of Soviet-American
relations or has a stronger foreign policy portfolio than our vice
president,'' Reagan said.
   ``So, on our get-together next week ... you can be sure I'll be
telling Mr. Gorbachev that George Bush represents change, yes, but
also continuity,'' Reagan said.
   Reagan's national security adviser, Lt. Gen. Colin Powell, says
U.S. officials expect no surprises at the luncheon meeting next
week, and that if Gorbachev presents some totally unexpected
proposal, as the Soviet leader did in Iceland two years ago, U.S.
officials will not allow themselves to be forced to make a snap
reply.
   The Reykjavik summit collapsed when Reagan and Gorbachev
disagreed over the Soviet leader's demand that the U.S. president
substantially downgrade his Star Wars missile-defense program.
   U.S. officials were widely criticized after the October 1986
summit, with political opponents accusing the American side of
having been unprepared to cope with Gorbachev's bold proposal.
   ``Based on what we have heard from the Soviets, I am not aware of
any that they're planning to put down on the table,'' Powell said.
   ``But I don't have, obviously, complete control over what the
general secretary might suggest,'' Powell continued. ``And if he
does have some ideas that we have not heard before, we will listen
carefully, respond or take them under advisement as the case may
be.''
   Powell also said that U.S. officials have ``no major new
proposals to put down on the table'' on Governors Island in New York
Harbor next Wednesday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
