<1ST_LINE>u i PM-AngolaTalks 1stLd-Writethru a0504 12-03 0564</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Angola Talks, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0504,0577</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Angola Talks Suspended Without Agreement</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with talks suspended. No pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BRAZZAVILLE, Congo (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Peace talks between Angola and South
Africa were suspended today after negotiations bogged down over how
to verify the withdrawal of 50,000 Cuban troops from Angola, South
African officials said.
   The talks were the latest round in U.S.-mediated efforts to end
hostilities between South Africa and Angola and to achieve
independence for South-West Africa, also known as Namibia.
   The spokesman for the South African negotiators, Roland Darroll,
said the South African, Angolan and Cuban delegations needed to
consult with their governments ``on essential questions which have
not been resolved.''
   The negotiators had hoped to sign an interim treaty Saturday
evening or Sunday. A formal treaty was to follow at a ceremony in
New York.
   In Johannesburg, the South African Press Association and
government-run television also reported the South African delegation
was returning home.
   The news agency quoted Foreign Minister Pik Botha of South Africa
as saying he was confident an agreement could be signed sometime
this month, but his delegation had to consult with President P.W.
Botha about proposals made on the issue of verification of Cuban
troop withdrawal from Angola.
   The television report, as well as an earlier report on
goverment-run radio, said Pik Botha would hold talks tonight with a
high-ranking Soviet foreign affairs official to work out snags in
the agreement.
   There was no report about whether those talks had taken place,
but South African television said the Soviet official, Deputy
Foreign Minister Anatoli Adamishin, was staying in the same hotel
where the talks were taking place.
   Such talks would be the first in decades between such
high-ranking officials from the two countries in a
publicly-acknowledged setting.
   South Africa and the Soviet Union have not met formally since
1956, when the Soviets broke diplomatic ties over South Africa's
system of apartheid.
   There have been frequent reports in the last two years of
lower-level contacts between the two nations to end longtime
conflicts in southern Africa. The Soviets, though not a party to the
peace talks, have usually had a delegation on hand to give advice to
their allies, Cuba and Angola.
   Botha briefly left the Brazzaville talks today to cross the Congo
River and deliver a message to Zaire's President Mobutu Sese Seko.
   Before departing, he told reporters the results of the talks will
depend on the attitude of the Cubans and Angolans. An Angolan
official, who declined to be further identified, said his delegation
still hoped ``for a happy ending.''
   The talks are aimed at achieving withdrawal of 50,000 Cuban
troops who are supporting the Marxist Angolan government in its
civil war against U.S.- and South African-backed guerrillas of the
National Union for the Total Independence of Angola, or UNITA. A
Cuban withdrawal is expected to lead to South African withdrawal
from South-West Africa, Angola's southern neighbor.
   South African officials say agreement has been blocked by a
disagreement over verification of the Cuban withdrawal.
   Pretoria has been insisting that it be allowed to participate in
monitoring the pullout, but Angola and Cuba have refused, saying the
United States can monitor the withdrawal and report to South Africa.
   Government-controlled South African radio said American
negotiator Chester Crocker, assistant secretary of state for African
affairs, was pressing South Africa to accept U.S. monitoring of the
withdrawal.
</TEXT>
