<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--Iraq-Medicine     12-03 0164</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Iraq-Medicine,0169</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iraq Institutes Fees for Medical Service</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government announced Saturday it will
impose fees for medical services for the first time in more than 50
years.
   The army daily Al-Qaddissiya said the new fees, approved by the
Health Ministry, took effect Thursday. They will cover all kinds of
services ranging from basic examinations to surgery at state
hospitals.
   The fee for a basic examination will be the equivalent of 60
cents, an X-ray about $1.60 and a baby delivery $3.20.
   Public medical service in Iraq has been free since it was started
in 1923.
   The new system is part of an effort by Baghdad to recoup heavy
economic losses stemming from its 8-year conflict with Iran. The
government borrowed up to $80 billion to fund the war. A cease-fire
began Aug. 20.
   The new medical fees also were seen as an attempt to cut down on
the number of people visiting doctors who are not truly sick.
</TEXT>
