<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Bolivia     12-03 0345</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bolivia,0355</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Dictator Ordered Arrested For Skipping Hearing On Guevara
Diary Theft</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER McFARREN</BYLINE>
<HEAD>Associated Press Writer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LA PAZ, Bolivia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities declared former ruler Luis
Garcia Meza a fugitive Saturday after he missed a congressional
hearing to testify on the theft of revolutionary Ernesto ``Che''
Guevara's diary.
   Garcia Meza, who has been under house arrest while facing trial
for theft and other charges, was to appear before the congressional
Justice and Police Commission in Sucre, 325 miles southeast of the
capital.
   The panel has accused Garcia Meza, a former army major general,
of stealing the diary of Guevara from a military safe and selling it
overseas. The diary covered Guevara's guerrilla activities up to his
death in 1967 in the hands of Bolivian military.
   The commission ordered his arrest when he failed to show up to a
Friday hearing. At a second hearing on Saturday his lawyer, Daniel
Salamanca, said in a statement that Garcia Meza refused to attend
and that the commission had no right to order his arrest.
   Col. Juan Ugarte, police commander in Sucre, told a local radio
station Saturday that his agents are searching for Garcia Meza and
have declared him a fugitive.
   Garcia Meza took over the government in 1980 after a bloody
military coup and ruled Bolivia until 1981 when military officers
removed him from office.
   The Supreme Court ordered his house arrest while trying him on
charges of human rights violations and theft between 1980 and 1981.
   Garcia Meza's administration was also accused by the United
States and other governments of involvement in cocaine trafficking.
   Guevara's diary was offered for sale by Sotheby's auction house
in England three years ago but the sale was suspended after the
Bolivian government filed legal briefs saying the diaries were the
property of the Bolivian government.
   Guevara, a Communist doctor from Argentina, helped lead the Cuban
revolution in 1959 and supported leftist guerrilla movements
worldwide. He later broke with Cuban President Fidel Castro and was
among rural revolutionaries hoping to overthrow Bolivia's government
when he was killed.
</TEXT>
