<2ND_LINE>AM-Germany-Train Crash,0172</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Train Crash In East Germany Kills Eight</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Polish freight train slammed into an East German
train carrying railroad workers Saturday, killing eight and
seriously injuring three, the state-run ADN news agency reported.
   The news agency said the engineer of the Polish train apparently
missed a signal to halt and rammed the East German train, which was
carrying railroad workers. The crash occurred in the town of
Goerlitz on the Polish border.
   Both diesel locomotives burst into flames after the crash and six
cars being pulled by the Polish train derailed, ADN said.
   ADN said the Polish engineer was killed, along with two other
Polish workers on the train. Another Pole was seriously injured.
Five people on the East German train were also killed, and two
seriously injured, ADN said.
   The injured were transported to hospitals in Goerlitz, ADN said.
   Another Polish worker on the train was treated for minor injuries
and released, ADN said. Goerlitz is 120 miles southeast of Berlin.
