<2ND_LINE>AM-South Korea-Hungary,0234</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hungary To Open Permanent Mission On Monday</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Communist Hungary sends its first
ambassador Monday, clearing the way for opening full diplomatic
relations with staunchly anti-communist South Korea, the Foreign
Ministry said Saturday.
   Ministry spokesman Kim Hang-kyung said Ambassador Sandor Etre
will arrive Monday to head his country's four-member mission. Etre,
47, served as Hungary's envoy to North Korea in 1979-84.
   Hungary became the first communist nation to open such a mission
in South Korea shortly before the 1988 Summer Olympics opened in
Seoul Sept. 17.
   The two countries, in announcing the decision, said they will
continue negotiations to open full diplomatic relations as soon as
possible.
   Following the announcement, South Korea set up its first mission
in Budapest in December last year.
   The decision stirred a diplomatic row between Hungary and South
Korea's archrival, communist North Korea. North Korea strongly
indicated it would sever relations with Hungary if Budapest goes
ahead with the decision.
   On Friday, the Soviet Union became the fifth East European nation
to sign agreements to exchange trade offices with South Korea, after
Hungary, Yugoslavia, Poland and Bulgaria, according to Seoul
officials.
   Under an accord signed in Moscow between South Korean and Soviet
officials, the two countries agreed to set up trade offices in each
other's capital in the first half of 1989, the officials said.
</TEXT>
