<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Soviet-China 1stLd-Writethru a0526 12-03 0585</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-China, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0526,0598</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chinese Official Says Cambodia `Hot Potato' In Sino-Soviet
Relations</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 5 grafs to UPDATE with Qian leaving for home;
Pickup 6th graf pvs, ``China wants...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ANN IMSE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chinese Foreign Minister Qian Qichen said Saturday
that his Soviet counterpart will travel to Beijing for more
discussions before the officials of the world's two largest
communist nations meet next year.
   Qian set no date or place for what would be a historic encounter
between President Mikhail S. Gorbachev and senior Chinese leader
Deng Xioping. Their nations have been estranged for three decades.
   ``Both sides agree believe it is important to hold such a
meeting,'' Qian told reporters at the conclusion of his three-day
visit to Moscow for meetings with Gorbachev and Soviet Foreign
Minister Eduard Shevardnadze.
   However, ``there are some outstanding issues which necessitate
further discussion,'' Qian said. ``For that reason, I have invited
my counterpart Mr. Shevardnadze to visit China early next year to
continue our discussions.''
   Qian, who left for home Saturday night, called the disagreement
between his country and the Soviet Union over Cambodia ``a hot
potato'' to be resolved before their planned summit.
   China wants the Soviet Union to persuade Vietnam to withdraw its
estimated 120,000 troops from Cambodia, where they have been
fighting Chinese-backed guerrillas for the past decade.
   Vietnam has committed itself to the withdrawal of 50,000 of its
forces by the end of this year and its remaining troops by 1990.
   Gorbachev told Qian on Friday he believed Vietnam is showing ``a
constructive spirit'' toward resolving the dispute, the official
Tass news agency reported.
   Qian said China is ready to negotiate directly with Vietnam over
the Cambodian dispute, but he added that some Vietnamese think
Cambodia ``is a dice to play'' in a game.
   ``We think it is not a dice but a hot potato. We think it is
better to throw out the hot potato.''
   Progress also has emerged on China's two other requirements for
improved relations with Moscow. Ongoing negotiations have settled
disputes over parts of the 2,600-mile border between China and the
Soviet Union. On another issue, half of the Soviet troops in
Afghanistan have been withdrawn.
   The Soviet Union sent troops into Afghanistan in December 1979 to
help the government fight the anti-communist rebels. Under Geneva
accords signed April 14 by Pakistan and Afghanistan, the Soviets are
to withdraw all of their military units by Feb. 15.
   However, the Soviets have threatened to disregard the Feb. 15
deadline if rebel fighting escalates. Tass said Gorbachev discussed
the Afghan issue with Qian Friday but gave no details.
   Qian's visit to Moscow was the first by a high-ranking Chinese
official in 31 years. China and the Soviet Union were allies in the
1950s, but relations soured over the direction of the world
communist movement. The tension peaked in 1969, when the two nations
fought a brief frontier war.
   Qian told reporters Saturday that China would like to normalize
relations ``on the basis of peace and coexistence,'' but without the
close ties that once bound the two nations.
   ``It is necessary not to go back to the period of the 1950s, but
it is also necessary not to return to confrontation,'' he said.
   During his 1-hour-40-minute meeting with Gorbachev and more than
six hours of meetings with Shevardnadze, Qian said the subjects
discussed also included border trade and joint exploration of the
Soviet Far East, as well as ``joint use of the labor force.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
