<1ST_LINE>u i AM-SriLanka     12-03 0547</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sri Lanka,0559</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>President Says He Will Dissolve Parliament, Call Elections</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEXTER CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sri Lanka's president said Saturday he
will dissolve Parliament Dec. 20, a day after presidential
elections, to give his successor ``the benefit of the views of the
present electorate.''
   President Junius R. Jayewardene also said he would call general
elections six months ahead of schedule, on Feb. 15 instead of the
scheduled balloting next August. He said new legislators would begin
their six-year terms March 9.
   Opposition parties and the powerful Buddhist clergy have urged
Jayewardene to disband Parliament before the presidential elections
in an effort to end the ethnic civil war that has wracked this
Indian Ocean island since 1983. Nearly 10,000 people have died in
the fighting.
   But Jayewardene has resisted their calls, saying he would
dissolve Parliament after his successor is chosen.
   ``I feel that an opportunity should be given to the people to
elect a new Parliament so that the new president should have the
benefit of the views of the present electorate,'' the 82-year-old
leader said in a speech broadcast on state-run radio and television.
   Jayewardene, who is ending a political career that spans 45
years, is prohibited by law from seeking a third six-year term.
   He and his United National Party have been in power since 1977,
extending their terms through a 1982 referendum rather than a
general election.
   A Sinhalese extremist group, the People's Liberation Front, has
called for the nation's estimated 9.3 million eligible voters to
boycott the presidential race, charging Jayewardene's government is
incapable of conducting a fair election.
   The front, a shadowy group known more for its violent acts than
its Marxist ideology, opposes a peace accord aimed at ending the
5-year-old insurgency by Tamil militants fighting for a separate
homeland in the north and east provinces. It also wants an estimated
47,000 Indian peacekeeping troops trying to supervise the accord
withdrawn from the island.
   Sinhalese extremists contend the accord grants too many
concessions to the Tamils, who are mostly Hindu and comprise 18
percent of Sri Lanka's 16 million people. The predominantly Buddhist
Sinhalese comprise 75 percent of the population and control the
government and the military.
   The front has vowed to kill anyone who supports the accord and
has been blamed for more than 900 political murders since the pact
was signed in July 1987. Most of the victims have been government
supporters.
   Earlier Saturday, Sri Lankan soldiers hunting for Sinhalese
rebels conducted a house-to-house search in the Colombo suburb of
Panadura after imposing a 22-hour curfew, which expires early Sunday.
   More than 100 suspects were taken into custody, but most were
released, according to a military official, who cannot be identified
under briefing rules. The operation was called after authorities
received information that front members planned to launch a
nationwide strike next week in an effort to destablize the
government.
   In his speech Saturday night, Jayewardene said political unrest
had hampered implementation of many of his government's programs.
   However, he told listeners: ``I value especially whatever I have
been able to do to preserve the rights of my people to elect their
representatives, to point out their mistakes and to replace them
through elections, thus preserving the fundamental freedoms of
democracy.''
</TEXT>
