<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Argentina Bjt   12-03 0666</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Argentina, Bjt,0685</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Alfonsin Says Won't Talk To Rebels</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto BAI1,2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM H. HEATH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Raul Alfonsin on
Saturday refused to negotiate with hundreds of rebel soliders holed
up at a giant army base and surrounded by loyal troops and tanks.
   Returning from a three-day trip to Mexico and the United States,
Alfonsin immediately met with top military aides and his Cabinet
``and gave instructions to re-establish discipline and order where
it has been broken,'' spokesman Jose Ignacio Lopez said.
   The president ``hopes the problem will be resolved in the course
of the day,'' but ``will not take any attitude that can be
interpreted as negotiation with the rebels,'' Lopez told reporters.
   The majority leader of the House of Deputies, Cesar Jaroslavsky,
who attended the meeting, told reporters later that Chief of Staff
Gen. Jose Dante Caridi asked Alfonsin whether his instructions meant
``that I must fight.''
   ``The president answered: `Do what you must do,''' Jaroslavsky
said.
   Caridi summoned army commanders to Buenos Aires for a meeting.
   Political, labor and civic leaders throughout the country urged
the government to use a firm hand in ending the two-day rebellion,
the third faced by Alfonsin since his election in 1983 to replace a
nearly eight-year military government.
   ``All the weight of the law must be brought to bear against those
who rise up with the arms the people gave them to defend the
constitution,'' said Eduardo Angeloz, the presidential candidate for
Alfonsin's ruling Civic Radical Union Party in elections set for
next May.
   At the giant Campo de Mayo base on the outskirts of Buenos Aires,
an estimated 450 rebels, armed with machine guns and automatic
weapons and led by Col. Mohamed Ali Seineldin, 54, remained in
control of an infantry school.
   Loyal troops, who fired several volleys of mortar shells at the
rebels on Friday, surrounded the school, supported by at least 16
medium tanks and armored personnel carriers.
   Although the army provided no figures on the number of troops
present, witnesses said loyal troops surrounding the infantry school
and in the base area appeared to number between 3,000 and 4,000.
   The army said in a communique that four military men were wounded
in exchanges of fire Friday, including a first lieutenant who was
listed in critical condition, a captain and two noncommissioned
officers. The army did not say to which band they belonged.
   Earlier, news agencies had reported that the first lieutenant was
killed.
   Local press reports indicated Friday night that a 19-year-old
woman walking on the base was wounded by gunfire.
   Vice President Victor Martinez announced Friday night that the
uprising ``had been overcome,'' but spokesmen for the rebels quickly
disputed that claim early Saturday.
   Roman Catholic Priest Luis Jardin, who claimed to be a ``personal
friend'' of Seineldin, left the infantry school early Saturday and
was quoted by the private news agency Noticias Argentinas as saying
that ``a truce of several days'' had been agreed on by the rebels
and Caridi.
   ``Seineldin has not surrendered nor does he intend to,'' said
Jardin.
   Seineldin, a combat veteran of the 1982 Falkland Islands War with
Britain, told reporters Friday he and his men did not want to
overturn the government, but sought to ``restore military honor to
the army and review the trials that punish the just and promote the
guilty.''
   A radio station in the northern province of Corrientes claimed to
have obtained a proclamation from rebel supporters which spelled out
demands.
   The rebels, Radio Provincia de Corrientes said, seek replacement
of the current general staff and an immediate end to trials of
military men accused of human rights abuses in a 1970s war against
leftist subversives. At least 9,000 Argentines ``disappeared''
during that time and are presumed dead.
   The station also said the rebels sought special budget treatment
for the armed forces. Army spending has been drastically slashed by
a government plagued by deficit spending, triple-digit annual
inflation and a $56 billion foreign debt.
</TEXT>
