<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Yugoslavia-Australia     12-03 0402</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Yugoslavia-Australia,0414</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Yugoslavia Protrsts Closure Of Consulate</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government strongly criticized
Australia on Saturday for closing the Yugoslav Consulate in Sydney
and expelling its staff, the state news agency said. But Yugoslavia
did not threaten to retaliate.
   Assistant Foreign Secretary Drago Mirosic made the protest to
Australian Charge d'Affaires Peter Shannon, who was summoned to the
Foreign Secretariat.
   The Foreign Secretariat ``most energetically protested'' the
Australian decision and ``expressed surprise and embitterment'' over
what was described as Australia's ``unilateral and unfounded
decision,'' the Tanjug news agency said.
   Australia on Friday shut the Yugoslav Consulate and ordered the
staff of 12 expelled following a diplomatic row over Yugoslavia's
refusal to surrender a security guard accused of shooting a
demonstrator.
   The Australian government had given the consulate 24 hours to
turn over the guard. When the deadline passed Friday, its foreign
minister, Gareth Evans, gave the staff and their dependents 72 hours
to leave the country.
   Evans said his government reserved the right to claim
compensation from Yugoslav officials for the family of Jospeh Tokic,
16, who was shot in the throat during a protest outside the
consulate Sunday, Yugoslav National Day.
   Yugoslav authorities said the guard, identified as Matijas Zoran,
fired in self-defense when several Croatian youths began scaling the
consulate walls. Croatians are among several ethnic groups in
Yugoslavia.
   About 200,000 Yugoslavs live in Australia.
   Tanjug quoted the Yugoslav protest as saying:
   ``The decision of the Australian authorities represents an act
which is inadequate to the character and level of the entire
relations between Yugoslavia and Australia and inflicts harm to the
preservation and further development of the relations between the
two countries.''
   It expressed ``regret that the proposal of the Federal Secretary
was not accepted (for Australia) to abandon ultimatum demands ...
(and) make possible through direct talks ... that a mutually
acceptable solution be found.''
   Yugoslavia also noted that no information had been received about
measures Australian authorities took to prevent further activity of
``pro-fascist emigres in Australia, directed against Yugoslavia and
its official representatives, as well as against the development of
stable relations between the two countries,'' Tanjug said.
   Yugoslavia emphasized that the responsibility for the current
situation in the two countries' relations rests with Australia.
   It said it ``reserves the right to take appropriate measures to
protect Yugoslav interests and dignity,'' but did not threaten to
retaliate against Australia for closing the consulate.
</TEXT>
