<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SatelliteMotor     12-03 0201</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Satellite Motor,0206</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Satellite Rocket For Next Shuttle Flight Damaged</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Space Shuttle, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A satellite rocket stage being
readied for the next space shuttle launch in February was badly
damaged when a worker bumped into it and will have to be replaced,
NASA announced Saturday.
   NASA spokesman George Diller said officials are assessing ``what
impact if any this incident might have on the planned Feb. 18
launch.''
   The stage is needed to boost a communications satellite to a high
orbit once the astronauts have released it from Discovery's cargo
bay.
   Diller said the worker bumped into the first stage nozzle and
cracked it during pre-launch checks Thursday.
   ``The Air Force and NASA have decided to replace the first stage
with a spare motor already available at the launch site,'' a space
agency statement said.
   Testing was to have begun Dec. 10 on the combined first and
second stages of the two-stage booster, Diller said.
   The tests will be delayed until about Dec. 27, he said, and
technicians probably would have to work two shifts a day seven days
a week to maintain the launch schedule. ``On paper, this plan seems
to work,'' Diller said.
</TEXT>
