<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Romania-Expulsions     12-03 0240</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Romania-Expulsions,0248</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Four Western Human Rights Activists Expelled From Romania</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Romania on Saturday expelled an
American, two West Germans and an Austrian after trying to meet with
Communist Party leader Nicolae Ceausescu's wife, a human rights
group reported.
   The four members of the International Society for Human Rights
were confronted by Romanian secret police at their hotel Saturday
morning and ordered to take an afternoon flight to East Berlin,
according to a statement issued by the Frankfurt-based group.
   Bill Ehart of Atlantic City, N.J.; Katarina Greab of Vienna,
Juerg Scheeser of Hamburg and Edgar Lamm of Bremen all had received
tourist visas and arrived in Bucharest on Friday, the organization
said.
   The group had attempted over the past few months to arrange a
meeting with Elena Ceausescu to present her with a list of more than
2,000 names of Romanians refused permission to join family members
in other countries. They also wanted to discuss a relaxation of
emigration rules, the group's statement said.
   No meeting with Mrs. Ceausescu had been agreed to by Romanian
officials.
   The human rights activists were told by secret police agents that
they had been ordered to leave because ``tourism has nothing to do
with anarchy,'' the society reported.
   It was not immediately clear what steps the group had taken to
meet with Mrs. Ceausescu.
   The four left Romania via Berlin aboard a jet of the East German
Interflug airline.
</TEXT>
