<1ST_LINE>r i AM-AngolaTalks     12-03 0472</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Angola Talks,0486</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Talks End Without Expected Agreement But Peace Process Continues</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRAZZAVILLE, Congo (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Southern African peace talks ended
without an accord Saturday when Angola, South Africa and Cuba failed
to agree on verification of a Cuban troop withdrawal from Angola.
   The U.S.-mediated talks were expected to produce an interim
accord.
   South African diplomats cited progress, but some members of the
U.S., Cuban and Angolan delegations appeared angry. Those members,
who declined to be further identified, questioned whether the South
Africans had any intention of negotiating an agreement.
   A South African spokesman, Roland Darroll, said the delegations
had to return home for further consultation with their governments
``on essential questions which have not been resolved.''
   The main issue remaining is verification of the withdrawal of
50,000 Cuban troops from Angola, which is scheduled to occur over a
27-month period.
   South African sources say they demanded representation on the
force monitoring the withdrawal, and have declined a U.S. offer to
observe and guarantee the pullout.
   Darroll said the failure to secure an agreement during these
talks should not be considered ``a rupture because progress has been
recorded. ... We will be returning to Brazzaville again with the
other delegations.''
   Although the South Africans sought to minimize the significance
of the failure to reach agreement, as late as Saturday afternoon
their Congolese hosts had been predicting an accord would be signed.
Ten days ago President Denis Sassou-Nguesso's government announced a
treaty would be signed Dec. 1.
   Failure to reach an accord threatens the latest deadline for
beginning the independence process for South-West Africa, also known
as Namibia, which borders South Africa.
   South Africa has said it would like to begin this process, which
will be supervised by the United Nations, by Jan. 1. However,
Pretoria has insisted the Cuban troops be withdrawn from Angola, the
territory's northern neighbor.
   The Cubans have helped Angola's Marxist government rebuff South
African invasions. The government also is battling the anti-Marxist
guerrillas of Jonas Savimbi, backed by South Africa, the United
States and other nations.
   The United States and several African nations have tried to
persuade Angola to negotiate with Savimbi, saying only
reconciliation can bring peace to the former Portuguese colony.
Angola has consistently refused to negotiate with Savimbi, who has
fought from his guerrilla strongholds since losing a struggle for
power following independence from Portugual in 1975.
   In Walvis Bay, South Africa, President P.W. Botha told a
community festival Saturday that the South African port surrounded
by the territory of South-West Africa will never become part of a
future independent Namibia.
   Botha said Walvis Bay is the most important harbor on the
southwest African coast between South Africa's naval headquarters at
Simonstown and the Angolan capital of Luanda. He said anyone
suggesting that it would not remain part of South Africa was talking
``nonsense.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
