<1ST_LINE>u i AM-AfghanTalks     12-03 0550</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Afghan Talks,0572</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviets and Afghan Guerrillas Hold Direct Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ABDULLAH AL-SHEHRI</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RIYADH, Saudi Arabia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Afghan guerrilla alliance held its
first direct talks with Soviet officials since Soviet troops were
sent to back the Marxist Afghan government in 1979.
   The head of the guerrilla delegation said the talks signaled the
failure of a U.N.-mediated accord to end the fighting.
   The talks began in Taif, a Saudi Arabian resort 600 miles from
Riyadh. The informal meeting is to be followed by formal
negotiations beginning later Saturday or Sunday, said sources close
to the talks.
   No details were immediately available about the meeting.
   The U.N.-mediated Geneva accord signed in April by the Soviet
Union and Pakistan called the Soviets' estimated 100,000 troops
backing the Marxist Afghan government to leave by Feb. 15.
   The first half left by August according to plan, but the Soviets
recently halted the pullout to protest continued operations by the
guerrillas, who have captured a number of cities.
   The Saturday meeting began after the arrival of Yuli Vorontsov, a
deputy foreign minister recently named ambassador to Afghanistan.
Vorontsov headed the Soviet delegation.
   Burhanuddin Rabbani, leader of a loose alliance of seven Afghan
resistance groups based in Peshawar, Pakistan, is the head of the
five-member guerrilla delegation.
   Rabbani, in a statement released Saturday in Pakistan, said
Moscow asked for the talks. He said his delegation planned to ask
the Soviets to withdraw the remaining Red Army troops from
Afghanistan immediately.
   ``The direct talks ... will mean the failure of the Geneva
accord,'' Rabbani said. The U.S.- and Pakistan-backed guerrillas
were not a part of the Geneva agreement.
   Rabbani said the delegation will also ask Moscow for ``payment of
war reparations,'' and ``the urgent removal of mines in the area
under Russian occupation.'' In addition the guerrillas want the
Soviets to supply maps of mined areas now under rebel control.
   Members of individual guerrilla groups met with Soviet officials
in Islamabad last month and in Bonn, West Germany, earlier this year
to discuss exchanging prisoners of war. This was the first direct
meeting with the guerrilla alliance.
   Saudi Arabia, a pro-Western kingdom, was chosen as a venue by the
Afghan resistance groups because of the influence it wields in the
Islamic world due to its oil wealth and control over Islam's two
holiest shrines.
   An official Saudi statement issued late Saturday, distributed by
the official Saudi press agency, said that the meeting was arranged
``at the mutual desire'' of the two sides and the aim was ``to
discuss issues pending between the two sides to reach a just
settlement of the Afghan problem.''
   Saudi leaders have tied the establishment of relations with
Moscow to a total pullout of Soviet troops from Afghanistan, a
Moslem state.
   Vladimir Petrovsky, also a Soviet deputy foreign minister, told a
press briefing in Moscow on Friday that the meeting was arranged by
the Saudi government with the cooperation of the Afghan government.
   It is aimed at finding ``ways for an internal Afghan
settlement,'' he said. However, he added that the meeting was not
connected to the international conference on demilitarization.
   Moscow and Afghan President Najib seek to convene an
international conference to demilitarize the country and set up a
coalition government with the guerrillas, who have rejected such a
conference.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
