<1ST_LINE>r i AM-UN-SovietBriefing     12-03 0451</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-Soviet Briefing,0464</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviet Briefing On Gorbachev Visit Heavy On Theory, Thin On Facts</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Gorbachev-At Home and Abroad, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A briefing Saturday by the advance team for
Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev turned into a display of
glasnost when team members disagreed whether the majority of Soviets
oppose Gorbachev's reforms.
   However, the Soviets could offer no clue to Gorbachev's schedule
of activities this week.
   The team's chief spokesman, Nikolai Yefimov, a senior ideologist
of the Communist Party Central Committee, insisted the team had no
more information on Gorbachev's visit, beginning with his arrival
Tuesday, than the reporters they addressed.
   Last week the Soviet U.N. Mission released a tentative schedule
for Gorbachev, but later withdrew it.
   Yefimov and five other officials even refused to speculate on
published reports that Gorbachev would meet billionaire real estate
developer Donald Trump or visit Wall Street while in New York.
   But Mark Zaharov, director of the Moscow Theater, said he would
like to see the Broadway play ``A Chorus Line'' to get some tips on
how to put on a hit musical.
   ``Our critics have been telling us that we too seldom put forward
any blockbusters. I would like to know whether you have a musical on
Broadway that has taken over from `A Chorus Line,''' said Zaharov.
   He said Gorbachev and his wife, Raisa, love the theater, but he
doubted their schedule would leave time for them to attend any
Broadway shows.
   The briefing epitomized Gorbachev's program for glasnost, or
openness, when the two officials disagreed on details of Soviet
reforms.
   Zaharov, a writer and director of the Lenin Council of the Moscow
Theater, said Gorbachev's reforms were not supported by a majority
of Soviets.
   ``In my personal feeling, very many people in our country don't
understand the importance of the processes that are going on in Mr.
Gorbachev's initiative,'' Zaharov said. ``I think he has more
opponents than supporters.
   ``I think in our country there is a lot of inertia still
prevailing, lack of initiative, and we are reaping the harvest of
some very difficult times in our history, and in this regard I am
somewhat pessimistic myself,'' he said.
   Yefimov disagreed.
   ``I don't share, I repeat, I don't entirely share the view of my
friend Mark Zaharov when he said that Gorbachev has more opponents
than supporters,'' Yefimov said.
   ``The forces of inertia are very great, and these forces of
inertia and these old habits are part of all of us. Maybe I'm too
optimistic, I don't know, but I can say with an absolutely clear
conscience that this (reform) machine is moving and is on its way,''
he said.
</TEXT>
