<2ND_LINE>AM-Cities Conference,0225</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Local Officials Plan To Press Urban Agenda</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's cities and towns will bear the burden
of government cutbacks unless the Bush administration raises more
revenue, said officials gathering Saturday for the National League
of Cities convention.
   Boston Mayor Raymond L. Flynn called the convention ``an
excellent opportunity to set an urban agenda for the nation's
cities.''
   More than 8,000 delegates from 1,300 local governments are
expected to attend the 65th annual convention of the country's
largest municipal organization.
   The convention formally begins Monday, with Massachusetts Gov.
Michael S. Dukakis, the unsuccessful Democratic candidate for
president, as one of the scheduled speakers. Randy Arndt, spokesman
for the league, said Saturday that Bush was invited to attend the
convention but did not accept the invitation.
   League President Pamela P. Plumb, a city councilor and former
mayor of Portland, Maine, said the nation's cities and towns ``will
bear the brunt of deficit reduction programs unless President-elect
Bush deals with revenue collection in a serious way.''
   Plumb said the league hopes to send strong signals to the Bush
administration that relationships betweeen local and federal
government need to be strengthened.
   Issues cited by delegates for discussion at the convention
include affordable housing, economic development, job training,
fighting inner-city drug use and improving education, she said.
</TEXT>
