<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Lebanon     12-03 0323</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lebanon,0336</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Moslem Prime Minister Calls Closing of Beirut Crossing `Sabotage'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head of the Moslem cabinet in
Lebanon's dual government said Saturday that the Christian decision
to close the only crossing linking the divided capital was
``sabotage.''
   The closure of the Museum Crossing was ordered Friday by
Christian army commander Gen. Michel Aoun to protest harassment by
Syrian-backed milities of soldiers moving from west Beirut to the
east side.
   The move has caused food and fuel shortages in west Beirut.
   ``This is an irresponsible act of sabotage,'' said acting Prime
Minister Salim Hoss, a Sunni Moslem. Aoun heads the three-member
Christian interim cabinet.
   A military source said Saturday the real reason behind Aoun's
move was the failure of the Central Bank, based in west Beirut, to
pay the November salaries of army personnel stationed in east
Beirut. Officials at the Central Bank declined to comment.
   The closure brought the daily truck supplies of flour and fuel
from Christian east Beirut to the Moslem sector to a standtill,
causing thousands of residents to crowd gas stations and bakeries to
stockpile on the commodities.
   It also was feared that the Christian army command would order a
blockade of drinking water. Water tanks, which supply both sides of
the capital, are based in east Beirut.
   The development aggravates a political crisis that threatens to
formalize the nation's de facto partition into two sectarian states.
   The crisis began when Parliament failed to elect a successor to
former President Amin Gemayel who, minutes before his term expired
on Sept. 22, appointed Aoun to head the interim cabinet.
   Syrian-backed Moslem leaders rejected Aoun's appointment, and
backed Hoss.
   Aoun's appointment, the Moslems charged, violated an unwritten
national covenant dating to Lebanon's independence from France in
1943. Under that pact, the premiership is given to the Sunni Moslem
sect, the presidency to the Maronite Christians and the position of
Parliament speaker to a Shiite Moslem.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
