<FILEID>AP-NR-12-03-88 1717EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SteinbergTrial     12-03 0745</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Steinberg Trial,0763</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Child-Murder Suspect's Scarred Companion Offers Riveting Testimony</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KILEY ARMSTRONG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hedda Nussbaum, a once-pretty woman whose face
and psyche bear the scars of what she describes as domestic torture,
has told of a sorrowful scenario that ended in death for 6-year-old
Lisa Steinberg.
   On Monday, Ms. Nussbaum, a former editor for Random House, will
return for a third day as the key prosecution witness in the trial
of her former companion, disbarred lawyer Joel Steinberg, who is
charged with murdering the illegally adopted child they raised as
their own.
   Her testimony, broadcast live by three local television stations
and recounted nationally, has described an 11-year relationship that
deteriorated with beatings, brainwashing, food deprivation and other
bizarre punishments for imagined transgressions.
   A 1981 photograph shows a smiling, vivacious, brown-haired, Hedda
Nussbaum who bears no resemblance to the woman now testifying:
gray-haired, with a boxer's nose, a cauliflower ear, a deformed
mouth, an injured eye.
   ``I'm hoping something positive will come out of it: more
support, more treatment and more awareness for women and for
children,'' said Janet Segal, director of clinical services at the
Four Winds Hospital in Katonah, where Ms. Nussbaum has received
psychiatric treatment since March.
   ``It's not something that can be treated with a pill or one or
two (therapy) sessions. It takes a lot of concerted effort.''
   In a slow, deliberate voice, punctuated by pain when she talks
about Lisa, Ms. Nussbaum, 46, has told how she came to view
Steinberg as a ``godlike figure'' _ asking his permission to eat,
obeying his orders to sleep on the floor or sit in a tub of cold
water.
   Jurors saw handwritten pages in which Nussbaum vowed to care
about Steinberg's hair, clothes, work, problems, diet, future, teeth
and other concerns. In another paper, she wrote 10 times that
``anger is destructive'' and that ``self-defense is regressive.''
   Steinberg convinced Ms. Nussbaum that she had belonged to a
sado-masochistic cult, then encouraged her to imagine the details
after convincing her she had amnesia, she testified.
   It was in this climate, the prosecution alleges, that an abused
and neglected Lisa was hurt on the night of Nov. 1, 1987. Hours
later, Joel Steinberg, smoking cocaine, admitted knocking the child
down and said it was because she stared at him, Ms. Nussbaum
testified. Lisa died four days later of a brain injury.
   Ms. Nussbaum was arrested with Steinberg after the little girl's
death, but charges against her were dropped and she agreed to
testify against him.
   The prosecution contends that Ms. Nussbaum, who lost her job when
she frequently missed work because of injuries and then spent most
of her time confined to the family's Greenwich Village apartment,
was herself too much of a victim to have helped the child.
   ``I can liken it to being a prisoner of war,'' Ms. Segal said
Saturday.
   The battered spouse syndrome, Ms. Segal said, is ``a process of
brainwashing where you end up not really knowing what you think,
what you believe, what's right, what's wrong. ... Gradually, there's
an erosion of spirit, of will, of judgment.''
   Its victims often are those who ``tend to be a bit timid,
possibly fearful of the unknown,'' she said.
   Testimony showed that Ms. Nussbaum tried to run away six times.
Once, she changed her mind because she feared violent retaliation,
she said. Once, a friend's brother told her she was being disloyal
to Steinberg; once, she went to a Connecticut social services
agency, where a staff member asked Steinberg to come get her.
   ``Generally, what you find is an alliance of sorts: physical or
emotional abuse, which is then, almost like a seesaw, balanced by
some occasional nurturing,'' said Ms. Segal. ``For a great many
women, if they did leave, where would they go _ especially with
children?'' In addition to Lisa, Ms. Nussbaum and Steinberg had
another illegally adopoted child, a boy who has since been returned
to his natural mother.
   Ms. Segal said patient confidentiality precluded her discussing
specifics of Ms. Nussbaum's case.
   ``She's been very courageous and is handling herself beautifully
_ that's my personal opinion,'' said Ms. Segal, adding that she also
had told that to Ms. Nussbaum.
   ``I think that now, people may feel a little safer talking about
some of this. It might encourage women to seek help, to try to get
out of eroding situations in their lives and to know that they're
not alone.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
