<HEAD>Football Stadium Scene Of Tribute To Six Who Died In Explosion</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 10 grafs to UPDATE with quotes, color from
ceremony. Picks up 6th graf pvs, `Sgt. Troy...'.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto KXA2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By AMANDA DAVIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of firefighters and police from
across the country paid tribute Saturday to six firefighters killed
in an explosion blamed on arsonists.
   ``They were willing and able to take risks in their every day
jobs for our protection, risk most of us would never dream of
taking,'' Mayor Richard Berkley told the mourners.
   ``So we owe these men a great deal. We owe them a commitment to
do everything in our power to prevent things like this from ever
happening again,'' the mayor said.
   Relatives of the six firefighters wiped away tears during parts
of the hour-long ceremony at Arrowhead Stadium. Flower arrangements
covered the stadium's field, where football's Kansas City Chiefs
play.
   The firefighters died Tuesday when about 50,000 pounds of
ammonium nitrate, a blasting agent, exploded at a highway
construction site.
   They had responded to a report that a pickup and construction
trailer were on fire. Witnesses have said they saw people prowling
in the area earlier.
   An estimated 2,500 firefighters and public safety officers and
5,000 private citizens attended the memorial, said fire department
spokesman Harold Knabe.
   Alfred Whitehead, president of the International Association of
Firefighters, spoke to the gathering in a trembling voice.
   ``As firefighters, we see death, destruction, pain and sorrow all
the time,'' said Whitehead. ``We don't usually share it with anyone
else, just ourselves.''
   ``But that doesn't mean we don't laugh, we don't love, we don't
cry, and we don't hurt.''
   Sgt. Troy Cole said police have received 50 to 75 tips, most of
them after Wednesday's announcement of a $35,000 reward. An
anonymous donor contributed $25,000.
   The men who died included two captains, Gerald C. Halloran, 57,
and James H. Kilventon Jr., 54, who between them had 66 years of
experience with the department.
   Funerals were held Friday for the captains and firefighters
Thomas McKarnin, 42, and Thomas M. Fry, 41. The rites for
firefighter Michael R. Oldham, 32, were Saturday, and those for
firefighter Luther E. Hurd, 31, will be Monday.
   On Friday, pumper trucks draped in black carried the first four
firefighters to their graves, with Halloran and Kilventon buried not
far from each other at a cemetery in suburban Raytown.
   ``It's difficult to try to reconcile the infinite love of God
with what's happened here,'' said Bishop John Sullivan of the Roman
Catholic Diocese of Kansas City-St. Joseph. ``We're called not just
to know God and to love him, but to trust him and put outselves in
his hands.''
   ``These men are very special,'' he said. ``These men labor not
much for monetary compensation but for the love of others.''
</TEXT>
