<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Dali     12-03 0332</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dali,0345</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ailing Artist Improving</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BARCELONA, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The condition of ailing surrealist
painter Salvador Dali is improving after nearly a week's
hospitalization for severe heart trouble and blood clots in a lung,
his doctors said Saturday.
   In a statement, a five-doctor team said the 84-year-old artist
``continues to improve favorably both from the clinical point of
view and that of the amount of oxygen in his blood.'' But they made
no predictions about his further recovery.
   On Monday, a police-escorted ambulance rushed the artist to the
Quiron Clinic here from a hospital in his hometown of Figueras, 60
miles north of Barcelona. He was listed in critical condition at
Quiron but began improving Thursday.
   He had entered Figueras Hospital on Sunday with pneumonia
stemming from a prolonged cold.
   Dali, a famous for his limp watches draped over dreamlike
landscapes, is the last member of an outstanding generation of
Spanish painters. They included Pablo Picasso, who died in 1973, and
Joan Miro, who died a decade later.
   One of Dali's doctors, Juan Garcia San Miguel, told reporters
that complications in the artist's condition could still arise ``but
now there is less of a possibility.
   ``He gets out of bed each day to sit up in a chair for a good
while,'' the doctor said.
   The statement said doctors will decide Monday whether to move
Dali out of the intensive care unit of the hospital.
   Since August 1984, Dali has been ailing as a result of burns he
suffered during a fire in the bedroom of his castle residence in La
Pera, 40 miles south of Figueras.
   After release from a hospital three months later, Dali moved to a
mansion attached to his Theater-Museum in Figueras.
   His brush with death left him bound to a wheel chair and eating
through a gastro-nasal tube. Since then, a team of nurses has kept
watch over him 24 hours a day.
   In July 1986, Dali underwent surgery in Barcelona to receive a
heart pacemaker.
</TEXT>
