<2ND_LINE>AM-Simon,0279</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Simon Says 1992 Presidential Bid Unlikely</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Paul Simon expects to have all his
presidential campaign debts paid off by early January, and he says
he'll probably sit out the 1992 race for the White House.
   Instead, Simon said in a radio interview taped Friday that he is
eager to ``start all over again'' on a campaign to retain his Senate
seat in 1990.
   Simon, D-Ill., said he has no problems with the Rev. Jesse
Jackson and does not expect a backlash from Jackson supporters when
he seeks re-election.
   Simon's presidential bid effectively ended after the Illinois
primary, in which he defeated fellow Illinoisan Jackson, but he kept
a hold on the delegates he won until the Democratic National
Convention.
   Some Jackson backers contend that Simon's refusal to release his
delegates after dropping out of the race undermined Jackson's broker
status at the convention.
   ``I don't think there will be much of a problem in 1990,'' Simon
said, in the radio interview which is to be broadcast Sunday on WBBM
radio. ``My voting record is clear on civil rights, things that are
important to minorities.''
   Jackson ``has earned his spurs'' within the Democratic Party and
should be viewed as one of the party's leaders, Simon said.
   Simon said his unsuccessful presidential bid cost about $11
million and he expects to have all campaign debts paid off by next
month.
   He said it is ``extremely unlikely'' that he would run for
president again in 1992. His immediate task is to start raising the
$6 million he expects to spend in the 1990 Senate race, Simon said.
</TEXT>
