<1ST_LINE>r a AM-AvtexAgreement     12-03 0430</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Avtex Agreement,0441</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Avtex, Attorney General's Office Reach Agreement</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Space Shuttle, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KAREN HAYWOOD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A company that makes a vital material used
in the space shuttle has signed a $17.75 million agreement that
settles lawsuits accusing it of contaminating water and exposing
workers to dangerous chemicals.
   The agreement, reached Friday with state officials, calls for
Avtex Fibers Inc. to comply with water quality laws, make its plant
safer for workers and pay $2 million in civil fines to the town of
Front Royal.
   ``We recognized the importance of the plant, with its 1,300 jobs
and the roles it plays in the space program and the national
security,'' said state Attorney General Mary Sue Terry.
   ``But our primary duty was to safeguard the environment and
protect the workers, of Front Royal, and of the commonwealth. To
accomplish that objective, we had to take a hard line.''
   Avtex spokesman Nick Nichols said Avtex managers were pleased to
put the lawsuits behind them. ``They now intend to go forward with
their business and take care of the various issues in these two
decrees,'' he said in a telephone interview from Washington.
   There was no answer Saturday at Avtex Chairman John N. Gregg's
home.
   The agreement, filed in two consent degrees in circuit courts in
Richmond and Warren County, includes $10 million in civil penalties
if the company fails to comply.
   The agreement settles two lawsuits field by the attorney
general's office. One filed for the Department of Labor and Industry
asked that Avtex be ordered to make certain repairs at the plant.
   The other lawsuit sought $19.7 million and was filed Nov. 2 on
behalf of the state Water Control Board for violations of the
company's national pollution discharge elimination permit. Avtex
closed the plant the next day, then reopened a week later after NASA
and the Pentagon guaranteed about $40 million in contracts.
   Avtex, the sole supplier of a type of rayon used in the space
shuttle, agreed to reduce employee exposure to carbon disulfide gas.
The chemical is used to make rayon and can cause a variety of
ailments, some fatal.
   It also agreed to stop discharging untreated wastewater from the
rayon process and to comply with existing and future pollution
discharge permits.
   Avtex is required to place $5.7 million in a trust fund to pay
for necessary repairs and changes.
   The provisions of the water quality settlement will be subject to
approval by the Water Control Board following 30 days for public
review, and approval by Gov. Gerald L. Baliles.
</TEXT>
