<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Plane-Cocaine     12-03 0192</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Plane-Cocaine,0196</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cocaine Found on U.S. Commercial Jetliner</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GUAYAQUIL, Ecuador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cleanup crews on a commercial jetliner
found almost 9 pounds of cocaine hidden under two seats, company
officials and police said Saturday.
   The judge leading the inquiry, Gabriel Noboa, ordered the Eastern
Airlines plane held at the airport in this port city until it was
known where the drug came from. No one was arrested.
   The L-1011 flew from Miami to Guayaquil, Ecuador, via Cali,
Colombia, Thursday night. The cocaine was found by cleanup crews
early the next morning, Eastern spokesman Robin Matell said in Miami
on Saturday.
   Gustavo Paez, local general manager of Eastern, appealed the
judge's decision immediately, according to company lawyer Jacinto
Velasquez. ``The drug was found out in the passengers' area and not
in the plane's luggage store,'' the lawyer said.
   Workers from a cleaning contractor found 8.8 pounds of cocaine in
two bags under two seats as they were cleaning the aircraft, police
and company officials said.
   Drug traffickers use Guayaquil as a center of operations. They
move drugs through the city that are bound for the United States and
Europe, according to officials.
</TEXT>
