<HEAD>King Nephew Stays At Church</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A congregation has voted to keep a
nephew of the Rev. Martin Luther King as its minister after the man
admitted he had undergone treatment for cocaine and alcohol abuse.
   The Rev. Derek King, 34, would have resigned if the congregation
of Tabernacle Missionary Baptist Church had offered a better
severance package, church officials said.
   A majority of deacons asked the nephew of the late civil rights
leader to resign after he announced from the pulpit two weeks ago
that he had completed the treatment program.
   But the congregation voted 107-68 on Thursday to keep King,
guaranteeing him the job for another year. He earns $26,000 annually
and pays no rent or utility bills.
   Before the meeting with the congregation, King and his attorney
met for 30 minutes with church officials discussing possible
severance pay options. But King wanted more money than church
officials offered, said Ulysses Kinsey, chairman of the bylaws
committee, and Deacon Alton Seymoure Jr.
   ``He was asking for too much and we weren't going to give him
that,'' Seymoure said.
   Church members who oppose King say they haven't given up their
fight to remove him, but King was hopeful.
   ``I will try to perform as best as I can to satisfy the
members,'' said King.
   Meanwhile, a group of ministers is trying to raise money for
King. His wife Janice is four months pregnant, and the family
apparently has little money.
