<1ST_LINE>r a AM-OSHAFine     12-03 0255</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-OSHA Fine,0261</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Connecticut Metal Company Fined In Acid Spill</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SOUTH WINDSOR, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A company where a worker died after
inhaling toxic fumes when he fell face-down in a puddle of a highly
corrosive form of acid will be fined $6,480 for various safety
violations, federal officials announced.
   Metals Testing Co. of South Windsor was cited for eight
infractions, some of which contributed to the October death, said
Brenda Gordon, industrial hygiene supervisor at the Occupational
Safety and Health Administration's Hartford office.
   The company tests metals for aircraft parts at its plant and uses
hydrofluoric acid to etch titanium parts.
   Timothy Cunningham, 29, of Hartford lost his footing in October
while carrying an open bucket of the acid and fell face-first into
the toxic, highly corrosive substance. Toxic inhalation was listed
as the cause of death, and his body was also burned.
   Two other workers were treated after inhaling the acid fumes.
   ``They (Metals Testing officials) didn't follow appropriate
working practices for handling corrosive materials,'' Gordon said
Friday. ``What caused the death was that the material spilled. It
wouldn't have spilled if it was being carried in a closed
container.''
   Company President Robert J. DeLisle declined comment on the OSHA
findings. The company can appeal the fines, Gordon said.
   OSHA said the citations alleged two counts of insufficient safety
training, two counts of lack of protective clothing, failure to
provide an appropriate first aid facility, failure to post safety
signs, improper labels on chemical tanks, and lack of a proper
eyewash station.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
