<2ND_LINE>AM-Trapped Filmmakers,0256</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Last of Trapped Filmmakers Freed From Cave</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PERTH, Australia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thirteen filmmakers trapped more than 250
feet underground in a desert cave slipped to safety one-by-one
through a tiny hole dug by rescuers on Saturday, authorities said.
   The group was trapped when a sudden rainstorm caused the mouth of
the cave to collapse as they were making a documentary film in an
isolated desert known as Nullarbor Plain in southwestern Australia.
   The last of the group emerged Saturday evening from a small
escape route that police said they had managed to dig. Police said
no one was injured.
   However, they described rescue conditions as very dangerous.
   ``It was raining and freezing cold, and they were afraid there
would be another cave-in at any time,'' said police spokesman David
Tree. ``The rescuers had to be very careful.
   ``Police made a hole big enough for them to squeeze through one
at a time, and they came out very slowly.''
   The group was filming a documentary on the system of caverns near
the tiny township of Cocklebiddy on Friday when the storm washed
away rocks, blocking the entrance to the cave.
   Tree said the group, all experienced cave explorers from their
mid-20s to 40 years old, were recovering from their ordeal in
Cocklebiddy.
   Eleven of the group were Australians, and one was from the United
States and one from England. They were identified.
   The Nullarbor is a huge, dry plain with an extensive cave system
underneath.
</TEXT>
