<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ChinaWhite     12-03 0285</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-China White,0293</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chemist Accused As China White Maker</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An synthetic narcotic similar to heroin that
caused at least 13 deaths was produced by a professional chemist in
a basement laboratory at the home he shares with his elderly
parents, authorities said.
   An informant led city, state and federal agents to the home of
Thomas Schaefers, 48, in suburban Aspinwall late Thursday, Assistant
U.S. Attorney Bruce Teitelbaum said Friday.
   Schaefers, jailed on a charge of drug manufacturing, is the
latest of 12 suspects arrested in connection with the drug
3-methyl-fentanyl, also known as China White.
   Besides the 13 deaths confirmed to be caused by the drug, it is
suspected in seven additional deaths.
   Teitelbaum said the informant claimed Schaefers made China White
with ingredients obtained at his job in a Calgon Corp. lab outside
Pittsburgh and from a pharmacist who wrote phony prescriptions.
   Teitelbaum did not identify the informant, who he said is an
addict who got the idea for making synthetic heroin from a
television news report nearly two years ago about so-called designer
drugs.
   The informant took the idea to Schaefers, who began working on
the compound in November 1987 and made a successful batch on his
third attempt, Teitelbaum said. In addition to that one-ounce batch,
Schaefers made a second, larger batch that netted him and the
informant $14,000 in profits, Teitelbaum said.
   Schaefers has a bachelor's degree in chemistry and has been a
staff chemist at Calgon's industrial water treatment research center
in Robinson Township since 1977, said company spokesman Tom Erdner.
   Calgon officials promised to cooperate with police.
   Six people suspected as leading distributors of the drug also
were arrested Thursday. Five others were charged earlier.
</TEXT>
