<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man threatening to blow the CBS network studios
to ``kingdom come'' demanded to read a statement on camera about a
child custody fight but surrendered an hour after the standoff began
Saturday, police said.
   It turned out the suitcase the man carried held ``a brick and a
bunch of wires,'' said Sgt. Ed Burns, a police spokesman.
   The man, Rocky Martuchi, 45, of Staten Island, was charged with
menacing and reckless endangerment, police said.
   Martuchi had entered the CBS Broadcast Center lobby and called
upstairs to the WCBS newsroom, saying, ``The law took my daughter
and I have a three-page letter I want to read to the cameras,''
according to Tom Farkas, assignment editor.
   ``I've got a suitcase here that would take this building into
kingdom come,'' Farkas quoted the man as saying.
   The man's letter outlined his problems stemming from a 1984
family court arrangement, said Deputy Police Inspector Peter
Scalabrino.
   Martuchi wanted to speak with a reporter, but agreed to allow a
police cameraman to make a videotape of his statement, the inspector
said.
   ``I think he wanted to get on camera to tell people what his
trouble was,'' Scalabrino said.
   The building on West 57th Street in mid-Manhattan also contains
CBS network studios and is the home of ``60 Minutes'' and ``West
57th Street.''
   An X-ray indicated that the item in the suitcase was only a
brick, police said. But as a precaution, the suitcase was not opened
until it was taken to a bomb disposal facility in the Bronx in a
special bomb-containment truck.
