<2ND_LINE>AM-Philippines-Rebels,0432</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Capture Rebel Leader Near U.S. Base</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CLARO CORTES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police captured a communist rebel
officer outside the U.S.-run Subic Bay naval base as he was on his
way to deliver weapons to guerrillas operating near the
installation, police said Saturday.
   Meanwhile, the military reported at least 21 people were killed
since Thursday in scattered clashes between government forces and
the New People's Army, which has been waging a 19-year insurgency to
establish a communist state in the Philippines.
   Police Lt. Col. MacArthur Torres said Roberto Tutanes, 35, a
political officer of the outlawed communist Party of the
Philippines, was apprehended Friday in a district of Olongapo, home
of the Subic Bay installation about 50 miles west of Manila.
   Torres, chief of the Olongapo district police command, said
Tutanes was carrying ammunition and was believed on his way to meet
local rebels when he was captured.
   Torres said Tutanes had been under surveillance for a month, and
the military had offered a $1,500 reward for his arrest.
   Also Saturday, the military said rebels ambushed a Philippine
army jeep near Orion on the Bataan peninsula, about 20 miles
southeast of Subic Bay.
   A Filipino company commander, Lt. Ruben Sarte, was killed and two
soldiers were wounded in the Thursday incident, the military said.
   About 13,000 U.S. troops, Defense Department civilians and
military dependents are permanently stationed at Subic, although the
number swells considerably when aircraft carriers and other vessels
call at the port.
   Subic is one of six American military installations in the
Philippines. In October 1987, rebels killed three Americans and a
Filipino of U.S. descent outside Clark Air Base, 50 miles north of
Manila.
   The rebels have threatened to attack other American military and
civilian personnel but have not killed more since the Clark
incident. The U.S. Embassy estimates there are up to 100,000
Americans living in the Philippines.
   In other engagements, three government militiamen and a civilian
were killed Friday when rebels attacked a military checkpoint near
Cauayan on Negros island, the military reported.
   The rebels burned the outpost before escaping with three M-16s,
five M-1 Garands, two Carbines, a grenade launcher and 2,000 rounds
of assorted ammunition, the military added.
   On Thursday, government forces claimed they killed 15 rebels when
guerrillas attacked a town hall. One policeman was also killed in
the battle, and nine soldiers were wounded later when guerrillas
ambushed troops sent to chase the rebels after the raid on the San
Jorge town hall.
</TEXT>
