<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel-Hanukkah     12-03 0243</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Hanukkah,0250</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Israel Begins Feast of Lights</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LOUIS MEIXLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Candles were lighted in the windows of homes
across the country Saturday as Jews began celebrating the eight-day
Festival of Lights, or Hanukkah, which commemorates the victory of
the Jews over the Syrians 2,000 years ago.
   Israel radio broadcast festive songs throughout the night, and
bakeries served the special sugar-coated jelly doughnuts that are a
holiday tradition.
   Hanukkah marks the victory of the Jews over the Greco-Syrian
kingdom in 165 B.C. The kingdom had tried to impose its culture on
the Jews and desecrated the holy temple in Jerusalem with statues of
Greek gods. The statues were regarded as pagan idols, which are
anathema to Jews.
   The Jews rose in revolt, destroyed the statues and drove the
Syrians out of Israel.
   According to legend, when the Jews tried to relight the temple's
eternal flame, they found enough oil for one day. But the fire
miraculously lasted for eight days.
   To commemorate the holiday, candles are lighted at sunset for
eight consecutive nights. They are placed one at a time in a special
eight-branch candelabra called a menorah.
   Fried foods such as potato pancakes and doughnuts are eaten to
commemorate the miracle of the oil.
   The festival is celebrated by religious and secular Jews as a
holiday that not only marks the ancient Jewish victory but also
reminds Israelis of their desire to perpetuate national Jewish
identity.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881203-0131 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-03-88 2222EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-NIreland-Arrest     12-03 0218</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-NIreland-Arrest,0223</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Charged In 14-Year-Old Ulster Killings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who gave himself up to
police in England was charged in Northern Ireland on Saturday with
the 1974 slayings of a woman soldier and a police detective.
   John Marian O'Callaghan, 34, a former local councilor in Tralee,
in the Republic of Ireland, walked into a police station in
Tunbridge Wells, south of London, on Thursday and was transferred to
the British province.
   He appeared, dressed in parka and jeans, at a special court in
Omagh, County Tyrone, amid tight security Saturday night.
   O'Callaghan was accused of murder in the killing of Eva Martin in
a mortar bomb attack on the Ulster Defense Regiment base in Clogher,
Country Tyrone, on May 2, 1974. Mrs. Martin was a Greenfinch, a
woman member of the UDR.
   O'Callaghan was also charged with murdering Detective Inspector
Peter Flanagan, who was shot to death in a pub in Omagh in August
1974.
   The suspect was ordered to appear in Magistrates Court Dec. 16.
   The predominantly Protestant province has been torn for two
decades by sectarian violence between the mainly Roman Catholic
Irish Republican Army and Protestant extremists. The IRA wants to
drive the British out of the province and unite it with the
overwhelmingly Catholic Republic of Ireland.
