<1ST_LINE>r a AM-People-Mitchelson     12-03 0261</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-People-Mitchelson,0269</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bar Files Disciplinary Charges Against Marvin Mitchelson</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Celebrity divorce lawyer Marvin Mitchelson has
been hit with new charges by the State Bar of California for
allegedly refusing to pay for $1 million in jewelry bought in
Switzerland.
   The two charges filed last week carry disbarment as the most
serious penalty, said Victoria Molloy, who filed the charges for the
Bar's office of chief trial counsel.
   Mitchelson is accused of bidding on two pieces of jewelry once
owned by the late Duchess of Windsor at an auction in Geneva in
April 1987 knowing that he did not intend to pay for them on time, a
written statement of the charges said.
   Bidders were told they had to pay for the items within seven
days, the statement said.
   In a second charge, Mitchelson allegedly told the auctioneer,
Sotheby's, that he would pay for the two items with an imminent fee
from a divorce case, the statement said.
   There was no home telephone number listed for Mitchelson. He did
not immediately return a call placed Saturday evening to his
answering service.
   However, Mitchelson said in court papers that Sotheby's had
agreed to extend credit to him and let him keep the jewelry.
   Nevertheless, Sotheby's accuses Mitchelson in court papers with
undue delays and lack of candor.
   The State Bar said last month that it had more than 20 complaints
about Mitchelson, including allegations of mishandling client money,
charging excess fees and failing to perform promised work. It said a
disciplinary hearing is expected to occur in January.
</TEXT>
