<FILEID>AP-NR-12-03-88 0141EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-JetEngineArt     12-03 0296</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Jet Engine Art,0304</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jet Set Artist Splatters Paint for Fine Arts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA ASHTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prince Juergen von Anhalt qualifies as a
jet-set artist in a literal sense.
   He creates his artwork by standing behind jet engines, throwing
buckets of paint into the air and having the high-velocity
propellant of the engines splatter the colors against his canvas.
   ``The paintings are of course abstract,'' von Anhalt said Friday.
   Their creation also is a little risky, because he has to stand in
the way of the jet's force.
   On Thursday, the platform he stood on at the New Orleans
Lakefront Airport, warming up for his performance today, upended
moments after he stepped out of the jets' 80 mph blast.
   ``Should debris go through the jet engines it could penetrate me
like a bullet,'' von Anhalt said. ``And then the fumes can be
intoxicating.''
   The German artist _ known as His Highness Juergen, prince von
Anhalt, duke of Saxony, count of Asconia and duke of Westphalia _
came to New Orleans at the invitation of grocery store magnate John
Schwegmann and his wife, Melinda.
   Using a Schwegmann-owned airplane, von Anhalt plans to perform
his techno-art today to create a work that will be raffled off for a
University of New Orleans fine arts scholarship fund.
   Von Anhalt will work on an 8-by-8-foot canvas with about 10
gallons of paint.
   Most of his fans say the paintings remind them of volcanoes, the
creation of light or something else explosive, said von Anhalt. Men
generally like his work better than women.
   ``I'm looking for a way to unite different elements,'' he said.
``Now, I'm uniting art with technology and I love what comes out. I
never name my pieces. I number them.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
