<HEAD>Teen-ager Held In Theft Of $50,000 Of Comic Books</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT WAYNE, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 13-year-old boy was being held in the
theft of about $50,000 worth of comic books, and the crime had
nothing to do with the youth's fascination with Wonder Woman or
Batman, a detective said.
   The teen-ager was arrested and some of the stolen books were
recovered Thursday, said police Detective Dan Camp.
   The thieves apparently knew which comics to take and their value,
Camp said.
   Another arrest and the recovery of several hundred more comics
was expected later, Camp said.
   The books were taken from Books, Comics and Things on Oct. 21 and
23. In the first break-in, a front window was broken and about
$2,000 worth of comics were snatched. In the second, a rock was
heaved through a side window, and high-priced comics dating back to
the early 1940s were taken.
   ``I've been beating the bushes for a month,'' Camp said. ``Not
just because it's my job, but because it torqued my jaws that they'd
hit it (the store) twice in three days.''
   News of the burglaries appeared in a comic-book collector trade
magazine, resulting in calls from dealers across the country
inquiring how to spot the missing books, said Tracy Scott, the
store's co-owner.
   The stolen comics included rare books published during World War
II featuring stories of superheroes pummeling Nazis and more modern
issues with tales of mutants battling masked villains.
   Some of the comics were found in a trash bin behind the store and
another set was left in a trash bag outside a home, police said.
   The youth was being held at the Wood Youth Detention Center.
