<1ST_LINE>r a AM-DeltaHearing     12-03 0502</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Delta Hearing,0515</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>FAA Officials Queried On Delay Of he Hot Seat</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE PEGO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>IRVING, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A hearing on the crash of Delta Flight 1141
closed Friday with Federal Aviation Administration officials asked
why their agency took weeks to distribute a safety bulletin for
takeoff warning systems.
   The Delta 727 crashed on takeoff Aug. 31 at Dallas-Fort Worth
International Airport, claiming 14 lives. Much of the probe has
turned on whether the plane's flaps were properly set for takeoff,
and whether a flap alarm system worked.
   FAA flight standards officer Ben Tollision was asked why his
office had taken weeks to distribute to Delta officials a bulletin
telling them to immediately service their takeoff warning systems on
Boeing 727s and 737s.
   The warning was prompted by the crash of Northwest Airlines
Flight 255 in Romulus, Mich. in 1987.
   Lane Chandler, principal operations inspector for the FAA's
southern region that oversees Delta Airlines, told the public
hearing Thursday his office had received the bulletin ``on Aug. 30,
or so.'' Delta Flight 1141 crashed Aug. 31 claiming 14 lives.
   The hearing concluded Friday night after about 33 hours of
testimony in which NTSB investigators interviewed experts in an
effort to gather infromation that might find a cause of the crash.
   Board member Jim Burnett said the NTSB will continue the
investigation although the hearing has concluded. The federal agency
continue accepting any new evidence until it drafts a final report
on the crash in about six months.
   Chandler sent a letter to Delta Vice President Harry Alger dated
Sept. 15, 1988, notifying him of ``aircarrier operations bulletin
No. 8-884, takeoff warning systems checks.''
   ``The accident in Dallas has focused the nation on the takeoff
warning system; therefore, we are requesting a little more than your
usual prompt reply,'' said Chandler in his letter to Alger.
   Chandler said in response to questions that ``sometimes it does
take a while to distribute information to working levels, to my
level,'' and explained he didn't specifically know how the June 17
letter was routed.
   Chandler said the bulletin would have been relayed through
several offices and reviewed by several individuals. ``I'm not sure
we call it a dead letter,'' Chandler said.
   Paul McCarthy of the Airline Pilot's Association said his group
was investigating whether the delay in spreading notice of the
inspections was normal or unusual.
   McCarthy also noted that the issue may only be on the periphery
of the public hearing. ``The testing is irrelevant to this
investigation only if it was a no-flap situation,'' McCarthy said.
``We continue to dispute this assertion.''
   ALPA has steadfastly maintained during the federal inquiry that
the three-man Delta crew, who testified earlier, were the victims of
a split-flap configuation in which the plane's outer flaps are
extended or in place for a takeoff while the inner flaps were not.
   A Boeing aerodynamics engineer testified earlier that he believes
Delta Flight 1141, given its recorded speed, could have achieved
flight even with no flaps.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881203-0152 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-03-88 0207EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Shuttle-BlueCube     12-03 0945</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Shuttle-Blue Cube,0966</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Inside Mysterious Blue Cube Scientists Track Military Satellites</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: First available for Saturday AMs</NOTE>
<HEAD>With PM-Space Shuttle, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVE WILSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SUNNYVALE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Step into the mysterious, windowless
Blue Cube, where 2,000 engineers and scientists working furiously
with old, slow computers will soon have a new task _ tracking and
controlling the $500 million spy satellite to be deployed by
Atlantis.
   Giant screens, rows of terminals and bulky machines fill a
warehouse-size room in the military's ultra-secret satellite
tracking center, receiving millions of bits of coded information
each second on the location and operation of hundreds of U.S., NATO
and foreign satellites.
   The Cube can order one of the more than 50 U.S. military
satellites to snap photos of suspected troop movements and drop off
the film in a parachute package to an Air Force plane for a midair
pickup. It can adjust a satellite's orbit, solar energy panels,
cameras or other gear.
   Special attention is focused now on the new ``bird'' to be placed
in orbit Saturday by the shuttle, a radar satellite code-named
Lacrosse that is designed to spy on the Soviet Union and guide the
stealth bomber.
   The Cube, officially called the Consolidated Space Test Center,
is run by the Air Force in the heart of Silicon Valley. Next door
are the NASA Ames Research Center and Lockheed Missiles & Space Co.
Inc.
   Neither journalists nor others without top security clearance are
allowed past the high fences and armed guards surrounding the pale
blue building. However, interviews with Air Force and NASA officials
with access to the Cube, all of whom asked not to be identified,
reveal a beehive of activity as a crack team of physicists,
electrical and mechanical engineers and computer scientists cope
with a crush of signals to and from satellites.
   ``The adrenalin flows, you work 18 hours a day, but you don't
feel tired at all,'' said one veteran of several satellite launches.
``You suffer battle fatigue when it's over, but during the mission
people get really hyped. This is their time and they're going to
make it work. When you run into obstacles because the system is
clumsy, just sheer energy makes it happen.''
   The Cube has been in operation since 1959, virtually from the
start of the space program. Despite the expenditure of several
hundred million dollars to upgrade the computer and data
distribution system over the past six years, most of the computers
in the Cube are two or three generations old.
   They are reliable workhorses, built by International Business
Machines Corp. and others in the 1970s and early 1980s, but are much
slower, less efficient and more expensive to run than newer models
at many companies in Silicon Valley.
   Instead of state of the art, the Cube's tubes and software
programs remain ``antiquated,'' one systems expert said, because of
government procurement policies.
   ``NASA and the military are stuck in this Catch-22,'' the systems
expert said. ``It's hard to sell missions and get money. So people
have to design minimal systems that use equipment from past
missions, and they end up putting systems in place that are terribly
engineered.''
   He added, though, that ``very exceptional people at NASA and the
military make the system work despite the system.''
   Until a few years ago, the Cube was the nation's only control
center for military satellites, a place so secret that officials
used to deny even its existence.
   Located within bazooka range of two highways and close to three
earthquake faults, the Cube's vulnerability led to a $3.5 billion
overhaul to bring it up to date and build a command center with
similar capabilities at Falcon Air Force Station in Colorado
Springs, Colo.
   Those two centers are linked to eight NASA tracking sites around
the world, including Guam, Spain and Australia, as well as other Air
Force stations and a main ground station at White Sands, N.M.
   The Tracking and Data Relay Satellite System, or TDRSS, is used
to keep watch over all satellites, friendly and unfriendly, and any
other ``space junk'' or debris from defunct satellites that could
get in their way.
   TDRSS West, a satellite in orbit 22,000 miles over the western
United States, was the main tracker in space until September, when
the shuttle Discovery placed TDRSS East in geosynchronous orbit
22,000 miles over the Atlantic.
   For the launch of the new spy satellite, the military and
civilian teams in the Cube and in Colorado Springs will take over
control of the satellite from NASA once they get the word ``the bird
is in orbit.''
   Because of secrecy requirements, nearly all the information from
the TDRSS satellites and the spy satellite is fully encrypted.
   The ground station at White Sands, a huge computer complex that
is perhaps the most modern communications facility in the world,
receives the information on two bands: C-band at 56,000 bits per
second and KU-band at 300 million bits per second. The system can
run several channels of each band simultaneously, taking in a total
of more than a billion bits of information per second.
   The signals are then broken up into multiple channels at lower
rates easier to handle, rebroadcast back up to military satellites
and down again to the Cube and Colorado Springs, where they are
monitored by the Air Force round the clock.
   The first job after the shuttle drops off the spy satellite is to
order the firing of positioning rockets to stabilize the satellite
in orbit.
   The exact position and type of orbit are secret, although some
experts call such secrecy ``a silly game,'' since Soviet tracking
stations can tell where all U.S. satellites are anyway.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
