<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Shuttle-Boosters     12-03 0414</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Shuttle-Boosters,0425</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Atlantis Rockets Heading Back To Cape</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Space Shuttle, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Atlantis' twin booster rockets were
heading back to land by way of sea today after helping send the
shuttle into space.
   Two ships towed the twin boosters toward Port Canaveral, near the
Kennedy Space Center, after they were recovered in rough seas 160
miles out in the Atlantic Ocean.
   They dropped with parachutes within eight miles of the recovery
ships after Friday morning's successful launch, the second since the
Challenger disaster blamed on booster rockets.
   ``Everything appeared to be very nominal (normal). There appeared
to be no external leakage or anything like that,'' said Jim Thomas,
a motor technical assistant for the Marshall Space Flight Center who
came to Kennedy Space Center for the launch.
   Divers from the recovery ships took a quick look at the boosters,
tossed in rough seas with winds of 20 to 30 knots, and saw no
obvious damage, said NASA spokesman George Diller.
   The divers removed the parachutes that slowed the boosters'
plummet, then attached flotation devices and cables from the
149-foot boosters to the two recovery ships and began removing
pockets of water, NASA said.
   The 200,000-pound steel casings were expected at Port Canaveral
this afternoon. After cleaning and other work here, they will be
returned to the Utah plant of manufacturer Morton Thiokol Inc. for
inspection and refitting.
   The boosters have drawn close attention since their failure was
blamed for the Jan. 28, 1986, Challenger explosion that killed all
seven astronauts aboard. The Rogers Commission that investigated the
disaster said a booster O-ring that failed to seal in cold weather
allowed flame to escape and ignited the main fuel tank.
   NASA spent $800 million to make 145 changes in the booster design
and for testing before the Discovery launch Sept. 29. The massive
rockets have 11 major components and are manufactured in four
segments joined at the seams.
   ``There are so many parts, so many things that could go wrong,''
said Thomas. But he added, ``I was not nearly as apprehensive'' as
he was during the Discovery launch. ``On that one, there was a lot
of apprehension. I stood there and cried.''
   When fully loaded with 1.1 million pounds of propellant, each
booster weighs 1.3 million pounds and produces 3.3 million pounds of
thrust that give the orbiter 80 percent of the power needed to lift
it from the launch pad into orbit.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
