<FILEID>AP-NR-12-03-88 0855EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a BC-WeeklyWallStreet Adv03-04   12-03 0677</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Weekly Wall Street, Adv 03-04,0698</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 03</NOTE>
<NOTE>$adv 04</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions Dec. 3-4</NOTE>
<HEAD>Searching for a Cure for Market Malaise</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOCA RATON, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In the closing weeks of 1988, Wall
Streeters are still groping for the right prescription to
reinvigorate a stock market that has languished all year.
   While the market's maladies have resisted all remedies, they have
not turned out as severe as they threatened to become after the
crash in October 1987.
   After all, barring a sudden sharp drop this month, stock prices
will close out this year, as they did last year, showing a net gain.
   But that prospect stirred little elation among the brokers who
gathered here this past week for the annual convention of their
principal trade group, the Securities Industry Association.
   Trading volume in all markets remains down, depressing a prime
source of the Street's revenues.
   Individual investors are still opting for the safe haven of
certificates of deposit or money market funds and shunning stocks.
   In addition, the gains the market has managed to record have
stemmed largely from takeover and buyout activity like the bidding
war for RJR Nabisco Inc. that has dominated recent financial
headlines.
   Whatever short-term benefits buyouts bring to brokers and their
customers, most analysts agree they have by no means solved the
problem of restoring confidence in the market.
   On the contrary, they have raised fears of new shocks when the
superstructure of debt created by the buyouts is sooner or later
tested in a business downturn.
   ``In the long term, I think it's unhealthy for the markets,''
said Joseph Hardiman, president of the National Association of
Securities Dealers, which supervises the over-the-counter market.
   Scandals over insider trading and other abuses also still cloud
the outlook.
   ``There is the matter of industry image, or reputation, or
integrity _ call it what you will,'' said Edward O'Brien, president
of the Securities Industry Association. ``It is undeniable that it
has been tarnished in the past few years.''
   While O'Brien argued that some criticisms of Wall Street's
behavior have gone beyond what is justified, he also acknowledged
that they have stung.
   ``In my view, there is no magic potion that can be taken to
produce a happy new world, and national media campaigns are not the
answer,'' he said.
   Then, too, there is the question of whether investigations and
reform measures since the 1987 market collapse have done enough to
restore faith in the mechanism of the marketplace itself.
   Arthur Levitt Jr., chairman of the American Stock Exchange,
thinks not. He urged that the new administration and Congress
appoint a commission to do a long-term study of the markets.
   More than 13 months after the fact, he said, ``I don't think
anyone understands last October.''
   Those who hold out hope for revived enthusiasm in the near future
say their conviction lies in the very caution and pessimism that are
so prevalent now.
   They point to measures of investment advisory sentiment that have
lately turned as gloomy as at any time since just before the start
of the 1982-87 bull market.
   And indeed, adherents of this school of ``contrary opinion'' made
their presence felt in the past week's trading activity.
   The Dow Jones industrial average of 30 industrials rose 17.60 to
2,092.28.
   The New York Stock Exchange composite index gained 2.39 to
153.02; the NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter market
added 7.53 to 373.91; and the Amex market value index was up 4.08 to
295.27.
   Volume on the Big Board averaged 132.54 million shares a day,
against 107.86 million the previous week.
   With so much money stockpiled in CDs and money market
investments, a drop in interest rates might well give stocks a big
lift, said John Bachmann, a St. Louis brokerage executive who was
chairman of the Securities Industry Association the past two years.
   In the crash, he said, ``the public was bruised and frightened,
but not broken. I suspect we could have a surprisingly good year in
1989.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Weekend Editions Dec. 3-4</NOTE>
</DOC>
